<TEI.2><TEIHEADER><FILEDESC><TITLESTMT><TITLE TYPE="245">The owl and the nightingale (MS Jes. Col. 29) [a machine-readable transcription]</TITLE><AUTHOR>Anonymous</AUTHOR></TITLESTMT><EDITIONSTMT><EDITION>The electronic text was created from an edited version of  MS Jes. Col. 29</EDITION></EDITIONSTMT><EXTENT>ca. 80 kilobytes</EXTENT><PUBLICATIONSTMT><DISTRIBUTOR>University of Michigan, Humanities Text Initiative</DISTRIBUTOR><IDNO>OwlJ</IDNO><AVAILABILITY><P>Available at URL http://www.hti.umich.edu/english/mideng/</P><P>This text has been made available through the Oxford Text Archive for personal scholarly use only.  OTA number:  U-1684-A</P></AVAILABILITY><DATE>1993</DATE></PUBLICATIONSTMT><SOURCEDESC DEFAULT="NO"><BIBLFULL DEFAULT="NO"><TITLESTMT><TITLE>The owl and the nightingale</TITLE><RESPSTMT><RESP>edited with introduction, texts, notes,  translation, and glossary</RESP><NAME>by J.W.H. Atkins</NAME></RESPSTMT></TITLESTMT><EXTENT>xc, 231 p. : ill. ; 23 cm.</EXTENT><PUBLICATIONSTMT><PUBLISHER>University Press</PUBLISHER><PUBPLACE>Cambridge</PUBPLACE><DATE>1922</DATE></PUBLICATIONSTMT><NOTESSTMT><NOTE PLACE="unspecified" ANCHORED="YES">Texts of the Cotton manuscript and the Jesus College,  Oxford MS 29 on opposite pages</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="unspecified" ANCHORED="YES">Authorship was formerly attributed  to Nicholas de Guildford</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="unspecified" ANCHORED="YES">The printed text contained illustrations  which are not noted in the electronic text</NOTE></NOTESSTMT></BIBLFULL></SOURCEDESC></FILEDESC><PROFILEDESC><CREATION><DATE>1190-1210</DATE></CREATION></PROFILEDESC><REVISIONDESC><CHANGE><DATE>February 17, 1994</DATE><RESPSTMT><NAME>Edward Gaynor</NAME><RESP>University of Virginia Library Cataloging Services Dept.</RESP></RESPSTMT><ITEM>TEI header revised</ITEM></CHANGE><CHANGE><DATE>January 1994</DATE><RESPSTMT><NAME>David Seaman</NAME><RESP>University of Virginia Library Electronic Text Center</RESP></RESPSTMT><ITEM>Tagging brought into line with the OTA.DTD, and parsed</ITEM></CHANGE><CHANGE><DATE>November 1993</DATE><RESPSTMT><NAME>Jamie L. Spriggs</NAME><RESP>University of Virginia Library Electronic Text Center</RESP></RESPSTMT><ITEM>paginated</ITEM></CHANGE><CHANGE><DATE>August 31, 1993</DATE><RESPSTMT><NAME>Edward Gaynor</NAME><RESP>University of Virginia Library, Cataloging Services Dept.</RESP></RESPSTMT><ITEM>TEI header completed</ITEM></CHANGE><CHANGE><DATE>July 1993</DATE><RESPSTMT><NAME>David Gants</NAME><RESP>University of Virginia Library Electronic Text Center</RESP></RESPSTMT><ITEM>UVa header added</ITEM></CHANGE><CHANGE><DATE>1990 or 1991</DATE><RESPSTMT><NAME>John Price-Wilkin</NAME><RESP>University of Michigan</RESP></RESPSTMT><ITEM>SGML tagging added</ITEM></CHANGE></REVISIONDESC></TEIHEADER><TEXT><BODY><HEAD>Incipit altercacio inter filomenam et Bubonem</HEAD><DIV1 TYPE="supplied line groups"><HEAD TYPE="supplied">Lines 1 through 100</HEAD><PB N="3"><MILESTONE N="229r.1" UNIT="folio"><L>ICH wes in one sumere dale</L><L>In one swi&thorn;e dyele hale</L><L>Iherde ich holde grete tale</L><L>An vle and one nyhtegale.</L><L N="5">&THORN;at playd wes stif &amp; starc &amp; strong</L><L>Sum hwile softe &amp; lud among;</L><L>And ey&thorn;er ayeyn o&thorn;er swal,</L><L>And let &thorn;at vuele mod vt al.</L><L>And ey&thorn;er seyde of o&thorn;res custe</L><L N="10">&THORN;at alre-w[u]rste &thorn;at hi ywuste:</L><L>&amp; hure &amp; hure of o&thorn;res songe</L><L>Hi holde playding swi&thorn;e stronge.</L><L>   &THORN;e Nihtegale bigon &thorn;o speke</L><L>In one hurne of one beche, <PB N="5"></L><L N="15">&amp; sat vp one vayre bowe,</L><L>&THORN;at were abute blostme ynowe,</L><L>In ore vaste &thorn;ikke hegge</L><L>I[m]eynd myd spire &amp; grene segge.</L><L>He wes &thorn;e gladder vor &thorn;e ryse,</L><L N="20">&amp; song a veole cunne wyse:</L><L>Bet &thorn;uhte &thorn;e drem &thorn;at he were</L><L>Of harpe &amp; pipe &thorn;an he nere:</L><L>Bet &thorn;uhte &thorn;at heo were ishote</L><L>Of harpe &amp; pipe &thorn;an of &thorn;rote,</L><L N="25">   &THORN;o stod on old stok &thorn;ar byside,</L><L>&THORN;ar &thorn;e vle song hire tyde,</L><L>And wes myd ivi al bigrowe:</L><L>Hit wes &thorn;are vle erdingstowe.</L><L>   &THORN;e Nihtegale hi iseyh,</L><L N="30">&amp; hi bi[hold] and ouerseyh,</L><L>&amp; &thorn;uhte wel ful of &thorn;are vle,</L><L>For me hi halt lodlich &amp; fule. <MILESTONE N="229r.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L>"Vnwyht," heo seyde, " awey &thorn;u fleo !</L><L>Me is &thorn;e wurs &thorn;at ich &thorn;e iseo.</L><L N="35">Iwis for &thorn;ine [vu]le lete</L><L>Wel ofte ich my song furlete; <PB N="7"></L><L>Min heorte atflyh&thorn; &amp; falt my tunge,</L><L>Hwenne &thorn;u art to me i&thorn;runge.</L><L>Me luste bet speten &thorn;ane singe</L><L N="40">Of &thorn;ine fule howelynge."</L><L>   &THORN;eos vle abod for hit wes eve,</L><L>Heo ne myhte no leng bileue,</L><L>Vor hire heorte wes so gret</L><L>&THORN;at wel neyh hire fnast atset,</L><L N="45">&amp; warp a word &thorn;ar-after longe;</L><L>"Hw &thorn;ynk &thorn;e nu bi [m]ine songe?</L><L>Wenestu &thorn;at ich ne kunne singe,</L><L>&THORN;e ich ne cunne of wrytelinge?</L><L>Ilome &thorn;u dest me grome,</L><L N="50">&amp; seist me bo&thorn;e teone &amp; schome.</L><L>If ich &thorn;e heolde on myne vote,</L><L>(So hit bitide &thorn;at ich mote!)</L><L>&amp; &thorn;u were vt of &thorn;ine ryse,</L><L>&THORN;u scholdest singe on o&thorn;er wise."</L><L N="55">   &THORN;e Nihtegale yaf onsware:</L><L>"If ich me loki wi&thorn; &thorn;e bare,</L><L>&amp; me schilde [w]it &thorn;e blete,</L><L>Ne recche ich nouht of &thorn;ine &thorn;rete: <PB N="9"></L><L>If ich me holde in myne hegge,</L><L N="60">Ne recche ich neuer hwat &thorn;u segge.</L><L>Ich wot &thorn;at &thorn;u art vn[m]ilde,</L><L>Wi&thorn; heom &thorn;at ne [m]uwe from &thorn;e schilde:</L><L>And &thorn;u tukest wro&thorn;e &amp; vuele,</L><L>Hwar &thorn;u myht ouer smale vowele. <MILESTONE N="229v.1" UNIT="folio"></L><L N="65">Vor&thorn;i &thorn;u art lo&thorn; al fowel-cunne      </L><L>&amp; alle heo &thorn;e dryue&thorn; heonne,</L><L>&amp; &thorn;e biscryche&thorn; &amp; bigrede&thorn;,</L><L>&amp; wel narewe &thorn;e bylede&thorn;:</L><L>&amp; ek for&thorn;e &thorn;e sulue mose,</L><L N="70">Hire &thorn;onkes, wolde &thorn;e totose.</L><L>&THORN;u art lodlich to biholde,</L><L>And &thorn;u art lo&thorn; in monye volde:</L><L>&THORN;i body is scort, &thorn;i swere is smal,</L><L>Gretture is &thorn;in heued ne &thorn;u al;</L><L N="75">&THORN;in eyen beo&thorn; colblake &amp; brode,</L><L>Ryht so hi weren ipeynt myd wode;</L><L>&THORN;u starest so &thorn;u wille abyten</L><L>Al &thorn;at &thorn;u myht myd clyure smyten;</L><L>&THORN;i bile is stif &amp; sarp &amp; hoked,</L><L N="80">Riht as on ewel &thorn;at is croked;</L><L>&THORN;armyd &THORN;u clechest euer among,</L><L>And &thorn;at is on of &thorn;ine song.</L><L>Ac &thorn;u &thorn;retest to myne vleysse,</L><L>Mid &thorn;ine cleures woldest me [m]eysse.</L><L N="85">&THORN;e were icundere to one frogge</L><L>&THORN;at sit at [m]ulne vnder cogge: <PB N="11"></L><L>Snayles, [m]us, and fule wihte,</L><L>Beo&thorn; &thorn;ine cunde &amp; &thorn;ine rihte.</L><L>&THORN;u sittest aday, and flyhst aniht,</L><L N="90">&THORN;u cu&thorn;est &thorn;at &thorn;u art on vnwiht.</L><L>&THORN;u art lodlich and vnclene,</L><L>Bi &thorn;ine neste ich hit mene,</L><L>And ek bi &thorn;ine fule brode,</L><L>&THORN;u vedest on heom a wel ful vode.</L><L N="95">Wel wostu &thorn;at hi do&thorn; &thorn;ar-ynne,</L><L>Hi fule&thorn; hit vp to &thorn;e chynne:</L><L>Heo sytte&thorn; &thorn;ar so hi beo bysne.</L><L>Hwarbi men segge&thorn; a vorbysne: <MILESTONE N="229v.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L>"Dehaet habbe &thorn;at ilke best</L><L N="100">&THORN;at fule&thorn; his owe nest."</L></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="supplied line groups"><HEAD TYPE="supplied">Lines 101 through 200</HEAD><L>&THORN;ot o&thorn;er yer a faukun bredde:</L><L>His nest nowiht wel he ne bihedde:</L><L>&THORN;arto &thorn;u stele in o day,</L><L>&amp; leydest &thorn;aron &thorn;i fule ey.</L><L N="105">&THORN;o hit bycom &thorn;at he hayhte,</L><L>&amp; of his eyre briddes wrauhte;</L><L>Heo brouhte his briddes mete,</L><L>Biheold his nest, iseyh hi ete: <PB N="13"></L><L>He iseyh bi one halue</L><L N="110">His nest ifuled in &thorn;e vt halue.</L><L>&THORN;e faukun wes wro&thorn; wi&thorn; his bridde,</L><L>&amp; lude yal and sturne chidde;</L><L>"Segge&thorn; me hwo haue&thorn; &thorn;is ido?</L><L>Eu nas neuer icunde &thorn;erto:</L><L N="115">Hit wes idon eu a lo&thorn;e custe.</L><L>Segge&thorn; me if ye hit wiste."</L><L>&THORN;o que&thorn; &thorn;at on and que&thorn; &thorn;at o&thorn;er:</L><L>"Iwis hit wes vre owe bro&thorn;er,</L><L>&THORN;at yeonde &thorn;at haue&thorn; &thorn;at grete heued:</L><L N="120">Way &thorn;at he nys &thorn;arof byreued!</L><L>Werp hit vt myd &thorn;e vyrste</L><L>&THORN;et his nekke him toberste!"</L><L>&THORN;e faukun leuede his ibridde,</L><L>&amp; nom &thorn;at fule brid amydde,</L><L N="125">&amp; warp hym of &thorn;an wilde bowe,</L><L>&THORN;at pie and crowe hit todrowe.</L><L>&THORN;erby men segge&thorn; a byspel,</L><L>&THORN;eyh hit ne beo fulliche spel;</L><L>Al so hit is bi &thorn;an vngode</L><L N="130">&THORN;at is icumen of fule brode, <PB N="15"></L><L>&amp; is ymeynd wi&thorn; freo monne,</L><L>Euer he cu&thorn; &thorn;at he com &thorn;enne, <MILESTONE N="230r.1" UNIT="folio"></L><L>&THORN;at he com of &thorn;an adel-eye,</L><L>&THORN;eyh he a freo neste leye.</L><L N="135">&THORN;eyh appel trendli from &thorn;e treo,</L><L>&THORN;ar he and o&thorn;er myde grewe,</L><L>&THORN;eyh he beo &thorn;ar-from bicume,</L><L>He cu&thorn; hwenene he is icume."</L><L>   &THORN;eos word ayaf &thorn;e nihtegale,</L><L N="140">And after &thorn;are longe tale</L><L>Heo song so lude &amp; so scharpe,</L><L>Ryht so me grulde schille harpe.</L><L>&THORN;eos vle luste &thorn;ider-ward,</L><L>&amp; heold hire eyen ne&thorn;er-ward,</L><L N="145">&amp; sat toswolle &amp; tobolewe,</L><L>So heo hedde one frogge iswolwe:</L><L>For heo wel wiste &amp; was iwar</L><L>&THORN;at heo song hire a-bysemar.</L><L>&amp; na&thorn;eles heo yaf ondsware,</L><L N="150">"Hwy neltu fleon in-to [&thorn;e] bare, <PB N="17"></L><L>And schewi hwe&thorn;er vnker beo</L><L>Of brihter hewe, of fayrur bleo ?"</L><L>"No, &thorn;u hauest scharpe clawe,</L><L>Ne kepe ich noht &thorn;at &thorn;u me clawe.</L><L N="155">&THORN;u hauest clyures swi&thorn;e stronge,</L><L>&THORN;u twengest &thorn;ar-mid so do&thorn; a tonge.</L><L>&THORN;u &thorn;outest, so do&thorn; &thorn;ine ilyche,</L><L>Mid fayre worde me biswike.</L><L>Ich nolde don &thorn;at &thorn;u me raddest,</L><L N="160">Ich wiste wel &thorn;at &thorn;u me misraddest.</L><L>Schomye &thorn;e vor &thorn;ine vnrede!</L><L>Vnwryen is &thorn;i swikehede !</L><L>Schild &thorn;i swike-dom from &thorn;e lyhte,</L><L>And hud &thorn;at wowe among &thorn;e ryhte.</L><L N="165">Hwanne &thorn;u wilt vnriht spene,</L><L>Loke &thorn;at hit ne beo isene: <MILESTONE N="230r.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L>Vor swikedom haue&thorn; schome and hete,</L><L>If hit is ope and vnder-yete.</L><L>Ne spedestu nouht mid &thorn;in vnwrenche,</L><L N="170">For ich am war and can blenche.</L><L>Ne helpe&thorn; noht &thorn;at &thorn;u bo to &thorn;riste:</L><L>Ich wolde vyhte bet myd liste <PB N="19"></L><L>&THORN;an &thorn;u mid al &thorn;ine streng&thorn;e.</L><L>Ich habbe, on brede &amp; ek on leng&thorn;e,</L><L N="175">Castel god on myne ryse:</L><L>" Wel fyht &thorn;at wel flyh&thorn;," sey&thorn; &thorn;e wise.</L><L>Ac lete [we] awey &thorn;eos cheste,</L><L>For suche wordes beo&thorn; vnwreste:</L><L>And fo we on myd rihte dome,</L><L N="180">Mid fayre worde &amp; myd some.</L><L>&THORN;eyh we ne beon at one acorde,</L><L>We mawe bet myd fayre worde,</L><L>Wi&thorn;vte cheste, and bute vyhte,</L><L>Playde mid so&thorn;e &amp; mid ryhte:</L><L N="185">&amp; may vr ey&thorn;er hwat he wile</L><L>Mid rihte segge &amp; myd skile."</L><L>   &THORN;o qua&thorn; &thorn;e vle, "Hwo schal vs seme,</L><L>&THORN;at cunne &amp; wille riht vs deme?"</L><L>"Ich wot wel" qua&thorn; &thorn;e nyhtegale,</L><L N="190">"Ne &thorn;arf &thorn;erof beo no tale.</L><L>Mayster Nichol of Guldeuorde,</L><L>He is wis and war of worde:</L><L>He is of worde swy&thorn;e glev,</L><L>And him is lo&thorn; eurich vn&thorn;eu. <PB N="21"></L><L N="195">He wot insyht in euche songe,</L><L>Hwo singe&thorn; wel, hwo singe&thorn; wronge:</L><L>And he con schede from &thorn;e rihte</L><L>&THORN;at wowe, &thorn;at &thorn;uster from &thorn;e lyhte."</L><L>   &THORN;e vle one hwile hi bihouhte</L><L N="200">And after &thorn;an &thorn;is word upbrouhte: <MILESTONE N="230v.1" UNIT="folio"></L></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="supplied line groups"><HEAD TYPE="supplied">Lines 201 through 300</HEAD><L>"Ich graunti wel &thorn;at he vs deme,</L><L>For &thorn;eyh he were hwile breme,</L><L>&amp; leof hym w[e]re Nihtingale,</L><L>And o&thorn;er wyhte gent &amp; smale,</L><L N="205">Ich wot he is nu [su]&thorn;e acoled.</L><L>Nis he vor &thorn;e nouht afoled,</L><L>&THORN;at he, vor &thorn;ine olde luue,</L><L>Me adun legge &amp; &thorn;e abuue:</L><L>N[e] schaltu neuer so him queme,</L><L N="210">&THORN;at he for &thorn;e fals dom deme.</L><L>He is nv ripe &amp; fastrede,</L><L>Ne luste hym nv to non vnrede:</L><L>Nv him ne lust namore pleye,</L><L>He wile gon a rihte weye."</L><L N="215">&THORN;e Nihtegale wes al ware,</L><L>Heo hedde ileorned wel ihware :</L><L>"Vle," heo seyde "seye me so&thorn;,</L><L>Hwi dostu &thorn;at vnwihtes do&thorn; ?</L><L>&THORN;u singest anyht &amp; nouht aday,</L><L N="220">And al &thorn;i song is waylaway. <PB N="23"></L><L>&THORN;u miht mid &thorn;ine songe afere</L><L>Alle &thorn;at here&thorn; &thorn;ine ibere:</L><L>&THORN;[u] scrichest &amp; yollest to &thorn;ine fere,</L><L>&THORN;at hit is gryslich to ihere:</L><L N="225">Hit &thorn;inche&thorn; bo&thorn;e wise &amp; snepe</L><L>Nouht &thorn;at &thorn;u singe [ac &thorn;at] &thorn;u wepe.</L><L>&THORN;u flyhst anyht and noht aday:</L><L>&THORN;arof ich wundri &amp; wel may.</L><L>For vych &thorn;ing &thorn;at schonye&thorn; riht,</L><L N="230">hit luuye&thorn; &thorn;uster &amp; hate&thorn; lyht;</L><L>&amp; euych &thorn;ing &thorn;at luue&thorn; misdede,</L><L>Hit luue&thorn; &thorn;uster to his dede.</L><L>A wis word, &thorn;eyh hit beo vnclene,</L><L>Is fele monne a-mu&thorn;e imene, <MILESTONE N="230v.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L N="235">For Alured King hit seyde &amp; wrot:  </L><L>"He schune&thorn; &thorn;at hine ful wot."</L><L>Ich wene &thorn;at &thorn;u dost al so,</L><L>For &thorn;u flyhst nyhtes euer mo.</L><L>[An] o&thorn;er &thorn;ing me is a-wene,</L><L N="240">&THORN;u hauest anyht wel bryhte sene:</L><L>Bi daye &thorn;u art stare-blynd,</L><L>&THORN;at &thorn;u ne syst bouh of lynd. <PB N="25"></L><L>Aday &thorn;u art blynd o&thorn;er bisne,</L><L>&THORN;arby men segge&thorn; a vorbisne:</L><L N="245">"Riht so hit far&thorn; bi &thorn;an vngode</L><L>&THORN;at nouht ne isyh&thorn; to none gode,</L><L>&amp; is so ful of vuele wrenche</L><L>&THORN;at him ne may no mon aprenche,</L><L>&amp; con wel &thorn;ene &thorn;ustre way,</L><L N="250">&amp; &thorn;ane bryhte lat away."</L><L>So do&thorn; &thorn;at beo&thorn; of &thorn;ine cunde,</L><L>Of lihte nabbe&thorn; hi none imunde."</L><L>   &THORN;eos vle luste swi&thorn;e longe,</L><L>&amp; wes ofteoned swi&thorn;e stronge:</L><L N="255">Heo qua&thorn; "&THORN;u hattest Nihtegale,</L><L>&THORN;u [m]ihtest bet hote galegale, <PB N="27"></L><L>Vor &thorn;u hauest to monye tale.</L><L>Let &thorn;ine tunge habbe spale!</L><L>&THORN;u wenest &thorn;at &thorn;es day beo &thorn;in owe:</L><L N="260">Let me nv habbe myne &thorn;rowe:</L><L>Beo nv stille &amp; let me speke,</L><L>Ich wile beo of &thorn;e awreke.</L><L>&amp; lust hw ich con me bitelle,</L><L>Mid rihte so&thorn;e wi&thorn;vte spelle.</L><L N="265">&THORN;u seyst &thorn;at ich me hude aday,</L><L>&THORN;arto ne segge ich nyk no nay:</L><L>&amp; lust ich telle hwervore,</L><L>Al hwi hit is &amp; hwarevore. <MILESTONE N="231r.1" UNIT="folio"></L><L>Ich habbe bile stif &amp; stronge,</L><L N="270">&amp; gode cleures scharp &amp; longe,</L><L>So hit bycume&thorn; to hauekes cunne</L><L>Hit is myn hyhte &amp; my [wu]nne</L><L>&THORN;at ich me drawe to mine cunde,</L><L>Ne may me no mon &thorn;arfor sende;</L><L N="275">On me hit is wel isene,</L><L>For rihte cunde ich am so kene.</L><L>Vor&thorn;i ich am lo&thorn; smale vowele</L><L>&THORN;at fleo&thorn; bi grunde &amp; bi &thorn;uuele: <PB N="29"></L><L>Hi me bichirme&thorn; &amp; bigrede&thorn;,</L><L N="280">&amp; heore flockes to me lede&thorn;.</L><L>Me is leof to habbe reste</L><L>And sitte stille in myne neste:</L><L>Vor nere ich neuer &thorn;e betere,</L><L>&THORN;eyh ich mid changling and myd chatere</L><L N="285">Heom schende &amp; myd fule worde,</L><L>So herdes do&thorn; o&thorn;er [m]id sit-worde.</L><L>Ne lust me wi&thorn; &thorn;e screwen chide;</L><L>For&thorn;i ich wende from heom wide,</L><L>Hit is a wise monne dome,</L><L N="290">&amp; hi hit segge&thorn; wel ilome,</L><L>&THORN;at me ne chide wi&thorn; &thorn;e gidie,</L><L>Ne wi&thorn; &thorn;an ofne me ne yonie.</L><L>At sum sy&thorn;e herde I telle</L><L>Hw Alured seyde on his spelle:</L><L N="295">"Loke &thorn;at &thorn;u ne beo &thorn;are</L><L>&THORN;ar changling beo&thorn; &amp; cheste vare;</L><L>Let sottes chide &amp; for&thorn; &thorn;u go."</L><L>&amp; ich am wis, &amp; do al so.</L><L>&amp; yet Alured seyde an o&thorn;er syde</L><L N="300">A word &thorn;at is isprunge wide,</L></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="supplied line groups"><HEAD TYPE="supplied">Lines 301 through 400</HEAD><L>"&THORN;at wi&thorn; &thorn;e fule haue&thorn; imene,</L><L>Ne cume&thorn; he neuer from him clene." <MILESTONE N="231r.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L>Wenestu &thorn;at hauek beo &thorn;e w[u]rse</L><L>&THORN;e crowe bigrede him bi &thorn;e mersche, <PB N="31"></L><L N="305">&amp; go&thorn; to him myd heore chyrme</L><L>Riht so hi wille wi&thorn; him schirme?</L><L>&THORN;e hauek folewe&thorn; gode rede;</L><L>He flyh&thorn; his wey, &amp; let hi grede."</L><L>   "[Y]et &thorn;u me seyst of o&thorn;er &thorn;inge,</L><L N="310">&amp; tellest &thorn;at ich ne can nouht singe,</L><L>Ac al my reorde is wonyng,</L><L>And to ihere gryslych &thorn;ing.</L><L>&THORN;at nis nouht so&thorn;, ich singe efne,</L><L>Mid fulle dreme &amp; lude stefne.</L><L N="315">&THORN;u wenest &thorn;at eoch song beo grislich</L><L>&THORN;at &thorn;ine pipinge nis ilich.</L><L>Mi stefne is bold &amp; nouht vnorne,</L><L>Heo is ilich one grete horne,</L><L>&amp; &thorn;in is iliche one pype,</L><L N="320">Of one smale weode vnripe.</L><L>Ich [singe] bet &thorn;an &thorn;u dest:</L><L>&THORN;u chaterest so do&thorn; on Yris prest.</L><L>Ich singe an efne a ryhte time,</L><L>&amp; se&thorn;&thorn;e hwenne hit is bed-time,</L><L N="325">&THORN;e &thorn;ridde sy&thorn;e a middel-nyhte:</L><L>&amp; so ich myne songe adihte</L><L>Hwenne ich iseo arise veorre</L><L>O&thorn;er day-rewe o&thorn;er day-steorre.</L><L>Ic do god myd myne &thorn;rote,</L><L N="330">And warny men to heore note.</L><L>Ac &thorn;u singest alle longe nyht,</L><L>From eue &thorn;at hit is day-liht,</L><L>&amp; euer leste&thorn; &thorn;in o song</L><L>So longe so &thorn;e nyht is long: <PB N="33"></L><L N="335">&amp; euer crowe&thorn; &thorn;i wrecche crey,</L><L>&THORN;at he ne swike&thorn; nyht ne day. <MILESTONE N="231v.1" UNIT="folio"></L><L>Mid &thorn;ine pipinge &thorn;u adunest</L><L>&THORN;as monnes eren &thorn;ar &thorn;u wunest,</L><L>&amp; makest &thorn;i song so vnwiht</L><L N="340">&THORN;at me ne telle&thorn; of &thorn;e nowiht.</L><L>Eurych mure&thorn;e may so longe leste,</L><L>&THORN;at heo schal liki wel vnwreste :</L><L>For harpe, &amp; pipe, &amp; foweles song</L><L>Mislike&thorn;, if hit is to long.</L><L N="345">Ne beo &thorn;e song ne so murie,</L><L>&THORN;at he ne sal &thorn;inche vnmurie</L><L>If he ileste&thorn; ouer vnwille:</L><L>So &thorn;u myht &thorn;i song aspille.</L><L>For hit is so&thorn;, Alured hit seyde,</L><L N="350">&amp; me hit may in boke rede:</L><L>"Eurich &thorn;ing may lesen his godhede</L><L>Mid vnme&thorn;e and ouerdede."</L><L>Mid este &thorn;u &thorn;e maist ouerquatie,</L><L>&amp; ouerfulle makie&thorn; wlatie: <PB N="35"></L><L N="355">&amp; euerich mure&thorn;e may agon,</L><L>If me hit halt euer in on,</L><L>Bute one, &thorn;at is Godes riche,</L><L>&THORN;a[t] euer is swete &amp; euer iliche:</L><L>&THORN;eyh &thorn;u nyme of &thorn;an lepe,</L><L N="360">Hit is euer ful by hepe.</L><L>Wunder hit is of Godes ryche,</L><L>&THORN;at euer spen&thorn; &amp; euer is iliche.</L><L>   Yet &thorn;u me seyst an o&thorn;er schome,</L><L>&THORN;at ich a[m] on [m]yne eye lome,</L><L N="365">&amp; seyst, for &thorn;at ich fleo bi nyhte,</L><L>&THORN;at ich ne may iseo bi lyhte.</L><L>&THORN;u liest! on me hit is isene</L><L>&THORN;at ich habbe gode sene:</L><L>Vor nys no so dym &thorn;esternesse</L><L N="370">&THORN;at ich euer iseo &thorn;e lesse.</L><L>&THORN;u wenest &thorn;at ich ne m[u]we iseo, <MILESTONE N="231v.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L>Vor ich bi daye nouht ne fleo.</L><L>&THORN;e hare lute&thorn; al day,</L><L>Ac no&thorn;eles iseo he may.</L><L N="375">If hundes eorne&thorn; to him-ward,</L><L>He genche&thorn; swi&thorn;e awey-ward,</L><L>&amp; hoke&thorn; pa&thorn;es swi&thorn;e narewe,</L><L>&amp; haue&thorn; mid him blenches yarewe.</L><L>He [hup&thorn;] &amp; start swi&thorn;e cove,</L><L N="380">&amp; seche&thorn; pa&thorn;es to &thorn;e groue:</L><L>Ne scholde he vor bo his eye</L><L>So do, if he &thorn;e bet ne iseye. <PB N="37"></L><L>Ich may iseo so wel so on hare,</L><L>&THORN;eyh ich bi daye sytte a dare.</L><L N="385">&THORN;ar auhte men beo&thorn; in worre,</L><L>&amp; fare&thorn; bo&thorn;e neor &amp; feorre,</L><L>&amp; ouervare&thorn; veole &thorn;eode,</L><L>&amp; do&thorn; bi nyhte gode neode,</L><L>Ich folewi &thorn;ane ahte manne,</L><L N="390">&amp; fleo bi nyhte in heore barme."</L><L>   &THORN;e nyhtegale in hire &thorn;ouhte</L><L>Atheold al &thorn;is, &amp; longe &thorn;ouhte</L><L>Hwat heo &thorn;arafter myhte segge:</L><L>Vor heo ne myhte noht alegge</L><L N="395">&THORN;at &thorn;e vle hedde hire iseyd,</L><L>Vor ho spak bo&thorn;e riht &amp; red.</L><L>&amp; hire of&thorn;uhte &thorn;at heo hadde</L><L>&THORN;e speche so feor uor&thorn; iladde,</L><L>&amp; wes aferd &thorn;at hire answare</L><L N="400">Ne w[u]r&thorn;e nouht ariht ivare.</L></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="supplied line groups"><HEAD TYPE="supplied">Lines 401 through 500</HEAD><L>Ac no&thorn;eles heo spak boldeliche,</L><L>Vor heo is wis &thorn;at hardeliche</L><L>Wi&thorn; his fo ber&thorn; grete ilete,</L><L>[&THORN;]at he for areh&thorn;e hit ne forlete: <PB N="39"></L><L N="405">Vor suych wor&thorn; bold if &thorn;u flyhst,</L><L>&THORN;at wile fleo if &thorn;u [ne] swykst; <MILESTONE N="232r.1" UNIT="folio"></L><L>If he isih&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;u [n]art areh,</L><L>He wile of bore wurche bareh.</L><L>&amp; for&thorn;i, &thorn;ey [&thorn;e] nyhtegale</L><L N="410">Were aferd, heo spak bolde tale.</L><L>   "[H]vle" heo seyde "hwi dostu so?</L><L>&THORN;u singest a-wynter wolawo !</L><L>&THORN;u singest so do&thorn; hen a-snowe,</L><L>Al &thorn;at heo singe&thorn; hit is for wowe.</L><L N="415">A-wintre &thorn;u singest wro&thorn;e &amp; yomere,</L><L>&amp; euer &thorn;u art dumb a-sumere.</L><L>Hit is for &thorn;ine fule ny&thorn;e</L><L>&THORN;at &thorn;u ne myht myd vs be bli&thorn;e,</L><L>Vor &thorn;u forbernest neyh for onde</L><L N="420">Hwenne vre blisse cume&thorn; to londe.</L><L>&THORN;u farest so do&thorn; &thorn;e ille,</L><L>Euerich blisse him is vnwille:</L><L>Grucching &amp; luring him beo&thorn; rade,</L><L>If he iseo&thorn; &thorn;at men beo&thorn; glade. <PB N="41"></L><L N="425">He wolde &thorn;at he iseye</L><L>Teres in eueriche monnes eye:</L><L>Ne rouhte [h]e &thorn;eyh flockes were</L><L>Imeynd bi toppes &amp; bi here.</L><L>Al so &thorn;u dost on &thorn;ire syde:</L><L N="430">For hwanne snouh li&thorn; &thorn;ikke &amp; wide,</L><L>&amp; alle wihtes habbe&thorn; sorewe,</L><L>&THORN;u singest from eue to a-morewe.</L><L>Ac ich mid me alle blisse bringe:</L><L>Ech wiht is glad for myne &thorn;inge,</L><L N="435">&amp; blesse&thorn; hit hwenne ich cume,</L><L>&amp; hihte&thorn; ayeyn myne cume.</L><L>&THORN;e blostme gynne&thorn; springe &amp; sprede,</L><L>Bo&thorn;e in treo &amp; ek in mede.</L><L>&THORN;e lilie myd hire fayre wlite</L><L N="440">Welcome&thorn; me, &thorn;eyh &thorn;u hit wite,</L><L>Bid me myd hire fayre bleo <MILESTONE N="232r.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L>&THORN;at ich schulle to hire fleo. <PB N="43"></L><L>&THORN;e rose also myd hire rude,</L><L>&THORN;at cume&thorn; of &thorn;e &thorn;orne wode,</L><L N="445">Bit me &thorn;at ich schulle singe</L><L>For hire luue one skentynge:</L><L>&amp; ich so do &thorn;ureh nyht &amp; day,</L><L>&THORN;e more ich singe &thorn;e more ich may,</L><L>&amp; skente hi myd myne songe,</L><L N="450">Ac no&thorn;eles nouht ouerlonge:</L><L>Hwenne ich iseo &thorn;at men beo&thorn; glade,</L><L>Ich nelle &thorn;at hi beon to sade:</L><L>Hwenne is ido for hwan ich com,</L><L>Ich vare ayeyn &amp; do wisdom.</L><L N="455">Hwanne mon howie&thorn; of his sheue,</L><L>&amp; falewi cume&thorn; of grene leue,</L><L>Ich fare hom &amp; nyme leue:</L><L>Ne recche ich nouht of wyntres teone.</L><L>Hwanne ich iseo &thorn;at cume&thorn; [&thorn;at] harde,</L><L N="460">Ich fare hom to myn erde,</L><L>&amp; habbe bo&thorn;e luue &amp; &thorn;onk</L><L>&THORN;at ich her com &amp; hider swonk.</L><L>Hwanne myn erende is ido,</L><L>Scholde ich bileue ? nay, hwarto ?</L><L N="465">Vor he nys no&thorn;er yep ne wis,</L><L>&THORN;at longe abid &thorn;ar him no neod is."</L><L>   &THORN;eos vle luste, &amp; leyde an hord</L><L>Al &thorn;is mot, word after word,</L><L>And after &thorn;ouhte hw heo myhte</L><L N="470">Onswere vynde best myd rihte:</L><L>Vor he mot ful wel him bi&thorn;enche,</L><L>&THORN;at is aferd of playtes wrenche.</L><L>   "&THORN;v ayssest me," &thorn;e vle seyde,</L><L>"Hwi ich a-winter singe &amp; grede. <PB N="45"></L><L N="475">Hit is gode monne ywune,</L><L>&amp; was from &thorn;e worlde frume, <MILESTONE N="232v.1" UNIT="folio"></L><L>&THORN;at ech god mon his frend iknowe,</L><L>&amp; blissi myd heom sume &thorn;rowe</L><L>In his huse at his borde,</L><L N="480">Mid fayre speche &amp; fayre worde.</L><L>&amp; hure &amp; hure to Cristesmasse,</L><L>Hwenne riche &amp; poure, more &amp; lasse,</L><L>Singe&thorn; cundut nyht &amp; day,</L><L>Ich heom helpe hwat ich may.</L><L N="485">&amp; ek ich &thorn;enche of o&thorn;er &thorn;inge</L><L>&THORN;ane to pleye o&thorn;er to singe.</L><L>Ich habbe herto god onsware</L><L>Anon iredi and al ware :</L><L>Vor sumeres-tyde is al wlonk,</L><L N="490">&amp; do&thorn; mysreken monnes &thorn;onk:</L><L>Vor he ne rek&thorn; noht of clennesse,</L><L>Al his &thorn;ouht is of golnesse:</L><L>Vor none dor no leng nabide&thorn;,</L><L>Ac euerich vp o&thorn;er ride&thorn;:</L><L N="495">&THORN;e sulue stottes yne &thorn;e stode,</L><L>Be&thorn; bo&thorn;e wilde and mare-wode.</L><L>&amp; &thorn;u sulf art &thorn;ar-among,</L><L>Vor of golnysse is al &thorn;i song,</L><L>&amp; ayeyn [&thorn;et &thorn;u wilt teme],</L><L N="500">&THORN;u art wel modi &amp; wel breme.</L></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="supplied line groups"><HEAD TYPE="supplied">Lines 501 through 600</HEAD><L>Sone so &thorn;u hauest itrede,</L><L>Ne myht &thorn;u leng a word ique&thorn;e,</L><L>Ac pipest al so do&thorn; a mose,</L><L>Mid cokeringe, mid stefne hose. <PB N="47"></L><L N="505">Yet &thorn;u singest w[o]rse &thorn;an &thorn;e heysugge,</L><L>&thorn;at flyh&thorn; bi grunde among &thorn;e stubbe:</L><L>Hwenne &thorn;i lust is ago,</L><L>&THORN;enne is &thorn;i song ago al so.</L><L>A-sumere chorles aweyde&thorn;</L><L N="510">&amp; uorcrempe&thorn; &amp; uorbrede&thorn;: <MILESTONE N="232v.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L>Hit nys for luue no&thorn;eles,</L><L>Ac is &thorn;eos cherles wode res;</L><L>Vo[r] hwanne he haue&thorn; ido his dede,</L><L>Ifalle is al his boldhede,</L><L N="515">Habbe he istunge vnder gore,</L><L>Ne last his luue no leng more.</L><L>Al so hit is on &thorn;ine mode;</L><L>So sone so &thorn;u sittest a-brode,</L><L>&THORN;u forleost al &thorn;ine wise.</L><L N="520">Al so &thorn;u varest on &thorn;ine ryse:</L><L>Hwenne &thorn;u hauest ido &thorn;i gome,</L><L>&THORN;i stefne go&thorn; anon to schome.</L><L>Ac hwenne nyhtes cume&thorn; longe,</L><L>&amp; brynge&thorn; forstes starke &amp; stronge,</L><L N="525">&THORN;anne erest hit is isene</L><L>Hwar is &thorn;e snelle, hwar &thorn;e kene.</L><L>At &thorn;an harde me may avynde</L><L>Hwo go&thorn; for&thorn;, hwo ly&thorn; bihynde.</L><L>Me may iseon at &thorn;are neode,</L><L N="530">Hwan me schal harde wike beode; <PB N="49"></L><L>&THORN;anne ich am snel, &amp; pleye &amp; singe,</L><L>&amp; hyhte me myd my skentinge:</L><L>Of none wyntre ich ne recche,</L><L>Vo[r] ich nam non aswunde wrecche.</L><L N="535">&amp; ek ich froueri fele wihte</L><L>&THORN;at myd heom nabbe&thorn; none [m]ihte:</L><L>Hi beo&thorn; houhful &amp; wel arme,</L><L>And seche&thorn; yorne to &thorn;en warme;</L><L>Ofte ich singe for hem &thorn;e more</L><L N="540">For lutly sum of heore sore.</L><L>Hw &thorn;ink&thorn; &thorn;e? artu [inome]?</L><L>Artu myd rihte ouercume ?"</L><L>   " Nay, nay ! " seyde &thorn;e Nihtegale,</L><L>"&THORN;u schalt ihere on o&thorn;er tale: <MILESTONE N="233r.1" UNIT="folio"></L><L N="545">Yet nis &thorn;eos speche ibroht to dome.  </L><L>Ac be stille, and lust nv to me:</L><L>Ich schal mid one bare worde</L><L>Do &thorn;at &thorn;i speche w[u]r&thorn; forwur&thorn;e."</L><L>   "&THORN;at nere noht riht" &thorn;e vle seyde,</L><L N="550">"&THORN;u hauest bicleped al so &thorn;u bede, <PB N="51"></L><L>And ich &thorn;e habbe iy[i]ue onswere.</L><L>Ac are we to vnker dome fare,</L><L>Ich wile speke toward &thorn;e</L><L>Al so &thorn;u speke toward me;</L><L N="555">&amp; &thorn;u me onswere if &thorn;u myht.</L><L>Sey me nv, &thorn;u wrecche wiht,</L><L>Is in &thorn;e eny o&thorn;er note</L><L>Bute &thorn;u hauest schille &thorn;rote?</L><L>&THORN;u nart nouht to non o&thorn;er &thorn;inge,</L><L N="560">Bute &thorn;u canst of chateringe:</L><L>Vor &thorn;u art lutel and vnstrong,</L><L>&amp; nys &thorn;i ryel nowiht long.</L><L>Hwat dostu godes among monne ?</L><L>Na mo &thorn;ene do&thorn; a wrecche wrenne.</L><L N="565">Of &thorn;e ne cume&thorn; non o&thorn;er god,</L><L>Bute &thorn;u gredest swich &thorn;u be wod:</L><L>&amp; beo &thorn;i piping ouergo,</L><L>Ne beo&thorn; on &thorn;e craftes na mo.</L><L>Alured seyde, &thorn;at wes wis:</L><L N="570">(He myhte wel, for so&thorn; hit is,)</L><L>"Nis nomon for his bare songe</L><L>Leof ne w[u]r&thorn; noht swi&thorn;e longe:</L><L>Vor &thorn;at is o furw[u]r&thorn;e man</L><L>&THORN;at bute singe naht ne can."</L><L N="575">&THORN;u nart bute o furw[u]r&thorn;e &thorn;ing:</L><L>On &thorn;e nys bute chateryng.</L><L>&THORN;u art dym &amp; of fule heowe,</L><L>&amp; &thorn;inchest a lytel soty clewe. <MILESTONE N="233r.2" UNIT="folio"><PB N="53"></L><L>&THORN;u nart fayr, ne &thorn;u nart strong,</L><L N="580">Ne &thorn;u nart &thorn;ikke, ne &thorn;u nart long;</L><L>&THORN;u hauest ymyst of fayrhede,</L><L>&amp; lutel is &thorn;i godhede.</L><L>An o&thorn;er &thorn;ing of &thorn;e ich mene,</L><L>&THORN;u [n]art feyr ne &thorn;u nart clene.</L><L N="585">Hwanne &thorn;u cumest to monne hawe,</L><L>&THORN;ar &thorn;ornes beo&thorn; &amp; ris idrawe,</L><L>Bi hegge &amp; bi &thorn;ikke weode,</L><L>&THORN;ar men go&thorn; to heore neode,</L><L>&THORN;arto &thorn;u draust [&thorn;ar]to &thorn;u w[u]nst</L><L N="590">&amp; o&thorn;er clene stude &thorn;u schunest.</L><L>Hwanne ich fleo nyhtes after muse,</L><L>Ich may &thorn;e vinde at &thorn;e rum-huse:</L><L>Among &thorn;e wede, among &thorn;e netle,</L><L>&THORN;u syttest &amp; singst bihinde seotle:</L><L N="595">&THORN;ar me &thorn;e may ilomest fynde,</L><L>&THORN;ar men worpe&thorn; heore byhinde.</L><L>Yet &thorn;u atwitest me myne mete,</L><L>&amp; seyst &thorn;at ich fule wyhtes ete.</L><L>Ac hwat etestu, &thorn;at &thorn;u ne lye,</L><L N="600">Bute attercoppe &amp; fule vlye,</L></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="supplied line groups"><HEAD TYPE="supplied">Lines 601 through 700</HEAD><L>&amp; wurmes, if &thorn;u myht fynde</L><L>Among &thorn;e volde of harde rynde?</L><L>Yet ich can do wel gode wike,</L><L>For ich can loki monne wike:</L><L N="605">&amp; mine wike beo&thorn; wel gode,</L><L>For ich helpe to monne vode.</L><L>Ich can nyme [m]us at berne,</L><L>&amp; ek at chireche in &thorn;e derne:</L><L>For me is leof to Cristes huse,</L><L N="610">To clansi hit wi&thorn; fule [m]use,</L><L>Ne schal &thorn;ar neuer cume to</L><L>Ful wiht, if ich hit may ivo. <MILESTONE N="233v.1" UNIT="folio"><PB N="55"></L><L>&amp; if me lust on my skenting</L><L>To wernen o&thorn;e[r] wunyng,</L><L N="615">Ich habbe at wode treon grete,</L><L>Mid &thorn;ikke bowe no&thorn;ing blete,</L><L>Mid ivi grene al bigrowe,</L><L>&THORN;at euer stont iliche iblowe,</L><L>&amp; his heou neuer ne uorleost,</L><L N="620">Hwanne hit snywe ne [hwanne hit] frost.</L><L>&THORN;arinne ic habbe god ihold,</L><L>A-wintre warm, a-sumere cold.</L><L>&THORN;ane myn hus stont briht &amp; grene,</L><L>Of &thorn;ine nys nowiht isene.</L><L N="625">Yet &thorn;u me telst of o&thorn;er &thorn;inge,</L><L>Of myne briddes seyst gabbinge,</L><L>&THORN;at heore [nest] nys nouht clene.</L><L>Hit is fale o&thorn;er wihte imene:</L><L>Vor hors a-stable, &amp; oxe a-stalle</L><L N="630">Do&thorn; al &thorn;at heom wile &thorn;ar valle.</L><L>&amp; lutle childre in &thorn;e cradele,</L><L>Bo&thorn;e cheorles &amp; ek a&thorn;ele,</L><L>Do&thorn; al &thorn;at in heore youh&thorn;e</L><L>&THORN;at hi uorlete&thorn; in heore duh&thorn;e.</L><L N="635">Hwat! can &thorn;at yongling hit bihede?</L><L>Yf hit mys[d]e&thorn;, hit mot nede:</L><L>A vorbisne is of olde iwurne,</L><L>&THORN;at neode make&thorn; old wif eorne. <PB N="57"></L><L>&amp; yet ich habbe an o&thorn;er onswere:</L><L N="640">Wiltu to myne neste vare</L><L>&amp; loki hw hit is idiht?</L><L>If &thorn;u art wis leorny &thorn;u mi[h]t:</L><L>Mi nest is holeuh &amp; rum amidde,</L><L>So hit is softest myne bridde.</L><L N="645">Hit is ibroyde al abute,</L><L>Vrom &thorn;e neste ueor wi&thorn;vte:</L><L>&THORN;arto hi go&thorn; to heore neode, <MILESTONE N="233v.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L>Ac [hwat] &thorn;u menest ich heom forbode.</L><L>We yeme nyme&thorn; of manne bure,</L><L N="650">&amp; after &thorn;an we makie&thorn; vre:</L><L>Men habbe&thorn; among o&thorn;re i[h]ende,</L><L>A rum-hus at heore bures ende,</L><L>Vor &thorn;at hi nelle&thorn; to veor go,</L><L>&amp; myne briddes do&thorn; al so.</L><L N="655">Syte nv stille, chaterestre !</L><L>Nere &thorn;u neuer ibunde vastre:</L><L>Herto ne vyndestu neuer answere.</L><L>Hong up &thorn;in ax! nv &thorn;u miht fare!"</L><L>   &THORN;e Nihtegale at &thorn;isse worde</L><L N="660">Was wel neyh ut of rede iwor&thorn;e,</L><L>&amp; &thorn;ouhte yorne on hire mode</L><L>Yf heo ouht elles vnderstode,</L><L>If heo cu&thorn;e ouht bute singe,</L><L>&THORN;at myhte helpe to o&thorn;er &thorn;inge. <PB N="59"></L><L N="665">Herto heo moste answere vynde,</L><L>O&thorn;er mid alle beon bihinde:</L><L>&amp; hit is strong to vyhte</L><L>Ayeyn so&thorn;e &amp; ayeyn rihte.</L><L>He mot gon to al mid gynne,</L><L N="670">Hwan &thorn;e horte beo&thorn; on winne:</L><L>&amp; &thorn;e man mot o&thorn;er segge,</L><L>He mot bihemme &amp; bilegge,</L><L>If mu&thorn; wi&thorn;vte may biwreo</L><L>&THORN;at me &thorn;e horte nouht niseo:</L><L N="675">&amp; sone may a word mysreke</L><L>&THORN;ar mu&thorn; schal ayeyn horte speke:</L><L>&amp; sone may a word myssturte</L><L>&THORN;ar mu&thorn; schal speke ayeyn horte.</L><L>Ac [no&thorn;eles hyet] upe &thorn;on,</L><L N="680">Her is to red hwo hyne con:</L><L>Vor neuer nys wit so kene</L><L>So hwanne red him is a-wene. <MILESTONE N="234r.1" UNIT="folio"></L><L>&THORN;anne erest cume&thorn; his yephede</L><L>Hwenne hit is alremest on drede;</L><L N="685">For Alured seyde of olde quide,</L><L>&amp; hyet hit nis of horte islide:</L><L>"Hwenne &thorn;e bale is alre-hekst,</L><L>&THORN;enne is &thorn;e bote alre-nest." <PB N="61"></L><L>Vor [w]it [w]est among his sore,</L><L N="690">&amp; for his sore hit is &thorn;e more.</L><L>Vor&thorn;i nis neuer mon redles</L><L>Ar his horte beo witles:</L><L>Ac if he furleost his wit,</L><L>&THORN;enne is his red-purs al to-slyt:</L><L N="695">If he ne con his wit atholde,</L><L>N[e] vynt he red in none volde.</L><L>Vor Alured seyde, &thorn;at wel cu&thorn;e,</L><L>Euer he spak mid so&thorn;e mu&thorn;e:</L><L>"Hwenne &thorn;e bale is alre-hekst,</L><L N="700">&THORN;enne is &thorn;e bote alre-nexst."</L></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="supplied line groups"><HEAD TYPE="supplied">Lines 701 through 800</HEAD><L>   &THORN;e Nihtegale al hi[re howe]</L><L>Mid rede hadde wel bitowe ;</L><L>Among &thorn;e harde, among &thorn;e towehte,</L><L>Ful wel myd rede hire bi&thorn;ouhte,</L><L N="705">&amp; hedde onswere god ifunde</L><L>Among alle hire harde stunde.</L><L>   "[U]le, &thorn;u axest me," heo seyde,</L><L>"[I]f ich con eny o&thorn;er dede</L><L>Bute syngen in sume tyde,</L><L N="710">&amp; bringe blisse veor &amp; wyde.</L><L>Hwy axestu of craftes myne ?</L><L>Beter is myn on &thorn;an alle &thorn;ine,</L><L>Beter is o song of myne mu&thorn;e</L><L>&THORN;an al &thorn;at [evre] &thorn;i kun ku&thorn;e:</L><L N="715">&amp; lust, ich telle &thorn;e hwarvore.</L><L>Wostu to hwan mon wes ibore?</L><L>To &thorn;are blisse of heueryche, <MILESTONE N="234r.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L>&THORN;ar euer is song &amp; [m]ureh&thorn;e ilyche: <PB N="63"></L><L>&THORN;ider funde&thorn; euerich man</L><L N="720">&THORN;at eny &thorn;ing of gode can.</L><L>For-&thorn;i me syng&thorn; in holy-chireche,</L><L>&amp; clerekes gynne&thorn; songes w[i]rche,</L><L>&THORN;at mon y&thorn;enche bi &thorn;e songe</L><L>Hwider he shal, &amp; &thorn;ar ben longe:</L><L N="725">&THORN;at he &thorn;e mureh&thorn;e ne voryete,</L><L>Ac &thorn;arof &thorn;enche &amp; bige[t]e,</L><L>&amp; nyme yeme of chirche stefne,</L><L>Hw [m]urie is &thorn;e blisse of heuene.</L><L>Clerekes, Munekes, &amp; canunes,</L><L N="730">&THORN;ar beo&thorn; &thorn;os gode wike-tunes,</L><L>Arise&thorn; vp to middel-nyhte,</L><L>&amp; singe&thorn; of &thorn;on heuene-lyhte:</L><L>&amp; preostes vpe londe singe&thorn;,</L><L>  *     *     *     *     *</L><L N="735">&amp; ich heom helpe hwat ic may,</L><L>Ich singe myd hem nyht &amp; day,</L><L>&amp; heo beo&thorn; alle for me &thorn;e gladdere,</L><L>&amp; to &thorn;e songe beo&thorn; &thorn;e raddure.</L><L>Ich warny men to heore gode,</L><L N="740">&THORN;at hi beon bly&thorn;e on heore mode,</L><L>&amp; bidden &thorn;at hi moten iseche</L><L>&THORN;at ilche song &thorn;at euer is eche.</L><L>Nu &thorn;u myht, vle, sitte and clynge:</L><L>Her-among nys no chateringe :</L><L N="745">Ich graunti &thorn;at &thorn;u go to dome</L><L>Tovore &thorn;e sulve Pope of Rome. <PB N="65"></L><L>Ac abid yete, no&thorn;eles,</L><L>&THORN;u schalt abyde on o&thorn;er [bles]:</L><L>Ne schaltu, vor Engelonde,</L><L N="750">At &thorn;isse worde me atstonde.</L><L>Hwy atwitestu me myne vnstreng&thorn;e,</L><L>&amp; myne vngrete, &amp; myn vnleng&thorn;e,</L><L>&amp; sayst &thorn;at ich am nouht strong, <MILESTONE N="234v.1" UNIT="folio"></L><L>Vor ic nam no&thorn;er gret ne long?</L><L N="755">Ac &thorn;u nost neuer hwat &thorn;u menest,</L><L>Bute lese wordes &thorn;u me lenest:</L><L>For ic kan craft &amp; ic kan lyste,</L><L>&amp; &thorn;arfore ic am &thorn;us &thorn;riste.</L><L>Ich kan wit &amp; song mony eine,</L><L N="760">Ne triste ic to non o&thorn;er mayne:</L><L>Vor so&thorn; hit is &thorn;at seyde Alured:</L><L>"Ne may no streng&thorn;e ayeyn red." <PB N="67"></L><L>Oft spet wel a lute lyste,</L><L>&THORN;ar muche streng&thorn;e solde myste;</L><L N="765">Mid lutle streng&thorn;e, &thorn;ureh ginne,</L><L>Castel &amp; bureh me may winne.</L><L>Mid liste me may walles felle,</L><L>&amp; werpe of horse knyhtes snelle.</L><L>Vuel streng&thorn;e is lutel w[u]r&thorn;,</L><L N="770">Ac wisdom ne w[u]r&thorn; neuer vnw[u]r&thorn;:</L><L>&THORN;u myht iseo &thorn;urh alle &thorn;ing,</L><L>&THORN;at wisdom naue&thorn; non euening.</L><L>An hors is strengur &thorn;an a mon;</L><L>Ac for hit non iwit ne kon,</L><L N="775">Hit ber&thorn; on rugge grete semes,</L><L>&amp; drah&thorn; bi sweore grete temes, <PB N="69"></L><L>&amp; &thorn;ole&thorn; bo&thorn;e yerd &amp; spure,</L><L>&amp; stont iteyed at mulne dure.</L><L>&amp; hit do&thorn; &thorn;at mon hit hot:</L><L N="780">&amp; for &thorn;an &thorn;at hit no wit not,</L><L>Ne may his streng&thorn;e hit ischilde</L><L>&THORN;at h[it] nabuh&thorn; &thorn;e lutle childe.</L><L>Mon do&thorn;, mid streng&thorn;e &amp; mid witte,</L><L>&THORN;at o&thorn;er &thorn;ing nys non his fitte.</L><L N="785">&THORN;ey alle streng&thorn;e at one [w]ere,</L><L>Monnes wit yet more were:</L><L>Vor &thorn;e mon myd his crafte, <MILESTONE N="234v.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L>Ouercume&thorn; al eor&thorn;liche shafte.</L><L>Al so ic do myd myne one songe</L><L N="790">Bet &thorn;an &thorn;u alle yer longe:</L><L>Vor myne crafte men me luuye&thorn;,</L><L>Vor &thorn;ine streng&thorn;e men &thorn;e schunye&thorn;.</L><L>Telstu bi me &thorn;e w[u]rs for &thorn;an</L><L>&THORN;at ic bute enne craft ne kan?</L><L N="795">If twey men go&thorn; to wrastlinge,</L><L>&amp; ey&thorn;er o&thorn;er vaste &thorn;ringe,</L><L>&amp; &thorn;e on can swenges swi&thorn;e fele,</L><L>&amp; kan his wrenches wel forhele,</L><L>&amp; &thorn;e o&thorn;er ne can sweng bute onne,</L><L N="800">&amp; &thorn;e is god wi&thorn; eche manne,</L></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="supplied line groups"><HEAD TYPE="supplied">Lines 801 through 900</HEAD><L>&amp; myd &thorn;an one ley&thorn; to grunde</L><L>Anne after o&thorn;e[r] a lutle stunde,</L><L>Hwat &thorn;arf he recche of a mo swenge,</L><L>Hwenne &thorn;e on him is so genge? <PB N="71"></L><L N="805">&THORN;[u] seyst &thorn;at &thorn;u canst fele wike,</L><L>Ac euer ich am &thorn;in vnyliche.</L><L>Do &thorn;ine craftes alle togadere,</L><L>Yet is myn on heorte betere.</L><L>Ofte hwan hundes foxes driue&thorn;,</L><L N="810">&THORN;e kat ful wel him sulue liue&thorn;,</L><L>&THORN;eh he ne cunne wreynch bute anne.</L><L>&THORN;e fo[x] so godne ne can nanne,</L><L>&THORN;ey he cunne so vele wrenche,</L><L>&THORN;at he wene&thorn; eche hunde atprenche.</L><L N="815">Vor he can pa&thorn;es rihte and wowe,</L><L>&amp; he can hongi bi &thorn;e bowe,</L><L>&amp; so vorlest &thorn;e hund his fore,</L><L>&amp; turn&thorn; eft ayeyn to &thorn;e more.</L><L>&THORN;e fox can crepe by &thorn;e heye,</L><L N="820">&amp; turne vt from his forme weye,</L><L>&amp; eft sone cume &thorn;arto: <MILESTONE N="235r.1" UNIT="folio"></L><L>&THORN;enne is &thorn;es hundes smel fordo:</L><L>He not, &thorn;urh &thorn;e [m]eynde smak,</L><L>Hwe&thorn;er he schal vor&thorn; &thorn;e abak.</L><L N="825">If &thorn;e uox miste of al &thorn;is dwele,</L><L>At &thorn;an ende he [creop&thorn;] to hole: <PB N="73"></L><L>Ac na&thorn;eles myd al his wrenche,</L><L>Ne can he hine so bi&thorn;enche,</L><L>&THORN;ey he beo yep &amp; swi&thorn;e snel,</L><L N="830">&THORN;at he ne leost his rede vel.</L><L>&THORN;e kat ne can wrench bute anne,</L><L>No&thorn;er bi dune ne bi venne:</L><L>Bute he can clymbe swi&thorn;e wel,</L><L>&THORN;armyd he were&thorn; his greye vel.</L><L N="835">Al so ich segge bi my seolue,</L><L>Beter is myn on &thorn;an &thorn;ine twelue."</L><L>   "Abid! abid!" &thorn;e vle seyde,</L><L>"&THORN;u gest al to mid swikelhede:</L><L>Alle &thorn;ine wordes &thorn;u bileyst</L><L N="840">&THORN;at hit &thorn;ink&thorn; so&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;u seyst:</L><L>Alle &thorn;ine wordes beo&thorn; isliked,</L><L>&amp; so biseme[d] and bilike[d],</L><L>&THORN;at alle heo &thorn;at hi auo&thorn;,</L><L>Hi wene&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;u segge so&thorn;.</L><L N="845">Abid! abid! me schal &thorn;e yene!</L><L>Nu hit schal w[u]r&thorn;e wel isene</L><L>&THORN;at &thorn;u hauest muchel ilowe,</L><L>Hwenne &thorn;i lesing beo&thorn; vnwrowe.</L><L>&THORN;u seist &thorn;at &thorn;u singest moncunne,</L><L N="850">&amp; techest heom &thorn;at hi funde&thorn; heonne</L><L>Vp to &thorn;e songe &thorn;at euer ilast:</L><L>Ac hit is alre w[u]ndre mest,</L><L>&THORN;at [&thorn;u] darst lye so opeliche.</L><L>Wenestu hi bringe so lyhtliche</L><L N="855">To Godes riche al singinde? <MILESTONE N="235r.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L>Nay! Nay! hi schule wel avynde <PB N="75"></L><L>&THORN;at hi myd longe wope mote</L><L>Of heore sunnen bidde bote,</L><L>Ar hi mote euer cume &thorn;are.</L><L N="860">Ich rede &thorn;i &thorn;at men beo ware,</L><L>&amp; more wepe &thorn;ane singe,</L><L>&THORN;at funde&thorn; to &thorn;an heuene-kynge:</L><L>For nys no mon wi&thorn;vten sunne.</L><L>For&thorn;i he mot ar he wende heonne,</L><L N="865">Mid teres &amp; myd wope bete,</L><L>&THORN;at him beo sur &thorn;at er was swete.</L><L>&THORN;arto ich helpe, God hit wot!</L><L>Ne singe ich heom no foliot:</L><L>Vor al my song is of longinge,</L><L N="870">And ymeynd sumdel myd woninge,</L><L>&THORN;at mon bi me hine bi&thorn;enche</L><L>&THORN;at he grony for his vnwrenche;</L><L>Mid myne songe ich hine [pulte],</L><L>&THORN;at he grony for his gulte.</L><L N="875">If &thorn;u gest herof to disputinge,</L><L>Ich wepe bet &thorn;an &thorn;u singe:</L><L>If riht go&thorn; for&thorn;, &amp; abak wrong,</L><L>Betere is my wop &thorn;an &thorn;i song.</L><L>&THORN;eyh summe men beon &thorn;urhut gode,</L><L N="880">&amp; &thorn;urhut clene on heore mode,</L><L>Heom longe&thorn; heonne no&thorn;eles.</L><L>&THORN;at beo&thorn; her, wo is hom &thorn;es:</L><L>Vor &thorn;eyh hi beo heom selue iborewe,</L><L>Hi ne seo&thorn; her nowiht bute serewe.</L><L N="885">Vor o&thorn;er men hi wepe&thorn; sore,</L><L>&amp; for heom bidde&thorn; Cristes ore. <PB N="77"></L><L>Ich helpe monne on ey&thorn;er halue,</L><L>Mi [m]u&thorn; haue&thorn; tweire kunne salue:</L><L>&THORN;an gode ich fulste to longinge, <MILESTONE N="235v.1" UNIT="folio"></L><L N="890">Vor hwenne him longe&thorn; ic him singe: </L><L>&amp; &thorn;an sunfulle ic helpe also,</L><L>Vor ic him teche hwar is wo.</L><L>Yet ic &thorn;e yene on o&thorn;er wise:</L><L>Vor hwenne &thorn;u sittest on &thorn;ine rise,</L><L N="895">&THORN;u drahst men to fleyses luste,</L><L>&THORN;at wil[l]e&thorn; &thorn;ine songes luste.</L><L>Al &thorn;u vorleost &thorn;e [m]ureh&thorn;e of heuene,</L><L>For &thorn;arto nauestu none steuene:</L><L>Al &thorn;at &thorn;u singest is of golnesse,</L><L N="900">For nys on &thorn;e non holynesse,</L></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="supplied line groups"><HEAD TYPE="supplied">Lines 901 through 1000</HEAD><L>Ne wene&thorn; no mon for &thorn;i pipinge</L><L>&THORN;at eny preost in chirche singe.</L><L>Yet ic &thorn;e wile on o&thorn;er segge,</L><L>If &thorn;u hit const ariht bilegge:</L><L N="905">Hwi nultu singe an o&thorn;er &thorn;eode,</L><L>&THORN;a[r] hit is muchele more neode?</L><L>&THORN;u neuer ne singest in Irlonde,</L><L>Ne &thorn;u ne cumest in Scotlonde.</L><L>Hwi nultu vare to Norweye,</L><L N="910">&amp; singen men of Galeweye? <PB N="79"></L><L>&THORN;ar beo&thorn; men &thorn;at litel kunne</L><L>Of songe &thorn;at is vnder sunne.</L><L>Hwi nultu &thorn;are preoste singe,</L><L>&amp; teche of &thorn;ire writelinge,</L><L N="915">&amp; wisi heom myd &thorn;ire stefne</L><L>Hw engles singe&thorn; in &thorn;e heuene?</L><L>&THORN;u farest so do&thorn; on an yde[l] wel</L><L>&THORN;at springe&thorn; bi burne &thorn;at is snel,</L><L>&amp; let fordruye &thorn;e dune,</L><L N="920">&amp; floh&thorn; an ydel &thorn;ar adune.</L><L>Ac ich fare nor&thorn; and sou&thorn;:</L><L>In euerich londe ich am cu&thorn;;</L><L>East &amp; west, sou&thorn; &amp; nor&thorn;, <MILESTONE N="235v.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L>I do wel fayre my mester,</L><L N="925">&amp; warny men mid myne bere,</L><L>&THORN;at &thorn;i dwele-song heo ne forle[r]e.</L><L>Ich wisse men myd myne songe,</L><L>&THORN;at hi ne sunegi nowiht longe;</L><L>Ich bidde heom &thorn;at heo iswike,</L><L N="930">&THORN;at heom seolue ne biswike:</L><L>For betere is &thorn;at heo wepe here,</L><L>&THORN;an elles hwar beo deoulene yuere."</L><L>   &THORN;e Nihtegale wes agromed</L><L>&amp; ek sum-del ofschomed,</L><L N="935">For &thorn;e vle hire atwiten hedde</L><L>In hwiche stude ho sat &amp; gradde,</L><L>Bihinde &thorn;e bure, among &thorn;e wed,</L><L>&THORN;ar men gon to heore ned; <PB N="81"></L><L>&amp; sat sum-del &amp; ho bi&thorn;ouhte,</L><L N="940">&amp; wiste wel on hire &thorn;ouhte</L><L>&THORN;e wra&thorn;&thorn;e binyme&thorn; monnes red.</L><L>For hit seyde &thorn;e king Alured:</L><L>"Selde ende&thorn; wel &thorn;e lo&thorn;e,</L><L>&amp; selde playde&thorn; wel &thorn;e wro&thorn;e."</L><L N="945">For wra&thorn;&thorn;e meyn&thorn; &thorn;e heorte blod</L><L>&THORN;at hit flowe&thorn; so wilde flod,</L><L>&amp; al &thorn;e heorte ouerge&thorn;,</L><L>&THORN;at heo naue&thorn; na&thorn;ing bute bre&thorn;,</L><L>&amp; so uorleost al his lyht,</L><L N="950">&THORN;at ho ne syh&thorn; so&thorn; ne riht.</L><L>&THORN;e nyhtegale hi vnderstod,</L><L>&amp; [o]uergan lette hire mod:</L><L>He myhte bet speken i-sele</L><L>&THORN;an myd wra&thorn;&thorn;e wordes dele.</L><L N="955">   "[H]vle," [heo] seyde "lust nv hider:</L><L>&THORN;u schalt falle, &thorn;i wey is slider.</L><L>&THORN;u seyst ich fleo bihinde bure: <MILESTONE N="236r.1" UNIT="folio"></L><L>Hit is riht, &thorn;e bur is vre:</L><L>&THORN;ar louerd ligge&thorn; and leuedy,</L><L N="960">Ich schal heom synge &amp; sitte bi.</L><L>Wenestu &thorn;at wise men forlete,</L><L>Vor fule venne, &thorn;e rihte strete?</L><L>Ne sunne &thorn;e later schyne,</L><L>&THORN;eyh hit beo ful in neste &thorn;ine?</L><L N="965">Scholdich, for one hole brede,</L><L>Furlete myne rihte stede, <PB N="83"></L><L>&THORN;at ich ne singe bi &thorn;e bedde,</L><L>&THORN;ar louerd haue&thorn; his lauedi bedde ?</L><L>Hit is my rihte, hit it my lawe,</L><L N="970">&THORN;at to &thorn;e hexste ich me drawe.</L><L>Ac if &thorn;u yelpst of &thorn;ine songe,</L><L>&THORN;at &thorn;u kanst yolle uro&thorn;e &amp; stronge,</L><L>&amp; seyst &thorn;u wisest monkunne,</L><L>&THORN;at hi biwepen heore sunne,</L><L N="975">Solde eueruych mon wony &amp; grede</L><L>Riht such hi weren vnlede?</L><L>Scholde hi yollen al so &thorn;u dest,</L><L>Hi myhten afere heore preost.</L><L>Mon schal beo stille &amp; noht grede;</L><L N="980">He mot biwepe his mysdede:</L><L>Ac &thorn;ar is Cristes heriynge,</L><L>&THORN;ar me grede &amp; lude singe.</L><L>Nis no&thorn;e[r] to lude ne to long,</L><L>At rihte tyme, chirche-song.</L><L N="985">&THORN;u yollest &amp; wonest, &amp; ic singe:</L><L>&THORN;i stefne is wop, &amp; myn skentinge.</L><L>Euer mote &thorn;u yolle &amp; wepen</L><L>&THORN;at &thorn;u &thorn;i lif mote forleten!</L><L>&amp; yolle mote &thorn;u so heye,</L><L N="990">&THORN;at ut tobersten bo &thorn;in eye!</L><L>Hwe&thorn;er is betere of tweyre twom, <MILESTONE N="236r.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L>&THORN;at mon beo bli&thorn;e o&thorn;er grom? <PB N="85"></L><L>So beo hit euer in vnker si&thorn;e,</L><L>&THORN;at &thorn;u beo sori &amp; ich bli&thorn;e.</L><L N="995">Yet &thorn;u ayschest hwi ic ne vare</L><L>Into o&thorn;er londe &amp; singe &thorn;are?</L><L>No! hwat scholdich among heom do,</L><L>&THORN;ar neuer blisse ne com to?</L><L>&THORN;at lond nys god, ne hit nys este,</L><L N="1000">Ac wildernesse hit is &amp; weste:</L></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="supplied line groups"><HEAD TYPE="supplied">Lines 1001 through 1100</HEAD><L>Knarres &amp; cludes houenetinge,</L><L>Snov &amp; hawel hom is genge.</L><L>&THORN;at lond is grislich &amp; vnuele,</L><L>&THORN;e men beo&thorn; wilde &amp; vnsele,</L><L N="1005">Hi nabbe&thorn; no&thorn;er gri&thorn; ne sibbe:</L><L>Hi ne recche&thorn; hw hi libbe.</L><L>Hi ete&thorn; fys &amp; fleys vnsode,</L><L>Suych wolues hit hadde tobroude;</L><L>Hi drinke&thorn; mylk &amp; hwey &thorn;arto,</L><L N="1010">Hi nute&thorn; elles hwet hi do: <PB N="87"></L><L>Hi nabbe&thorn; noht wyn ne beor,</L><L>Ac libbe&thorn; al so wilde deor:</L><L>Hi go&thorn; bytuht myd rowe felle,</L><L>Riht suych hi come vt of helle.</L><L N="1015">&THORN;ey eny god man to heom come,</L><L>So hwile dude sum from Rome,</L><L>For heom to lere gode &thorn;ewes,</L><L>&amp; for to lete heore vn&thorn;ewes,</L><L>He myhte be[t] sytte stille,</L><L N="1020">Vor al his hwile he scolde spille:</L><L>He myhte bet teche ane beore</L><L>To bere scheld and spere,</L><L>&THORN;ane &thorn;at wilde volk ibringe</L><L>&THORN;at hi me wolde ihere singe.</L><L N="1025">Hwat scholdich &thorn;ar mid myne song[e], <MILESTONE N="236v.1" UNIT="folio"></L><L>Ne singe ic heom neuer so longe,</L><L>Mi song were ispild vych del:</L><L>For heom ne may halter ne bridel</L><L>Bringe from here wode wyse,</L><L N="1030">Ne mon mid stele ne mid i[s]e. <PB N="89"></L><L>Ac &thorn;ar lond is este and god,</L><L>&amp; &thorn;ar men habbe&thorn; mylde mod,</L><L>Ic notye myd heom [m]ine &thorn;rote,</L><L>For ic may do &thorn;ar gode note:</L><L N="1035">&amp; bringe heom leue tydinge,</L><L>For ic of chirche-songe singe.</L><L>Hit wes isayd in olde lawe,</L><L>&THORN;at yet ilast &thorn;ilke so&thorn;-sawe,</L><L>&THORN;at mon schal eryen &amp; sowe,</L><L N="1040">&THORN;ar he wene&thorn; after god mowe:</L><L>For he is wod &thorn;at sowe&thorn; his sed</L><L>&THORN;ar neuer gras ne spring&thorn; ne bled."</L><L>   &THORN;e vle wes wro&thorn;, to cheste rad,</L><L>Mid &thorn;isse worde hire eyen abraid:</L><L N="1045">"&THORN;u seyst &thorn;u witest monne bures,</L><L>&THORN;ar leues beo&thorn; &amp; fayre flures,</L><L>&THORN;ar two yleoue in one bedde</L><L>Ligge&thorn; iclupt &amp; wel bihedde.</L><L>Enes &thorn;u sunge, ic wot wel hware,</L><L N="1050">Bi one bure, &amp; woldest lere</L><L>&THORN;e leuedi to an vuel l[u]ue,</L><L>&amp; s[u]nge bo&thorn;e lowe &amp; buue, <PB N="91"></L><L>&amp; leredest hi to don schome</L><L>&amp; vnriht of hire lichome.</L><L N="1055">&THORN;e louerd &thorn;at sone vnderyat,</L><L>Lym &amp; grune &amp; wel ihwat,</L><L>Sette &amp; leyde &thorn;e for to lacche.</L><L>&THORN;u come sone to &thorn;an hacche,</L><L>&THORN;u were ynume in one grune, <MILESTONE N="236v.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L N="1060">Al hit abouhte &thorn;ine schine :      </L><L>&THORN;u neddest non o&thorn;er dom ne lawe,</L><L>Bute myd wilde hors [were] todrawe.</L><L>Vonde if &thorn;u myht eft mysrede,</L><L>Hwe&thorn;er &thorn;u wilt, wif &thorn;e meyde:</L><L N="1065">&THORN;i song mai beo so longe genge</L><L>&THORN;at &thorn;u schalt hwippen on a sprenge."</L><L>   &THORN;e Nihtegale at &thorn;isse worde,</L><L>Mid swerde &amp; myd speres orde,</L><L>If heo mon were, wolde vyhte:</L><L N="1070">Ac &thorn;o heo bet do ne [m]ihte,</L><L>Heo vauht myd hire wise tunge.</L><L>"Wel viht &thorn;at wel spek&thorn;" sey&thorn; in &thorn;e songe.</L><L>Of hire tunge heo nom red:</L><L>" Wel viht &thorn;at wel spek&thorn;" seyde Alured.</L><L N="1075">   "Hwat! seystu &thorn;is for ruyne schome?</L><L>&THORN;e louerd hadde herof grome.</L><L>He wes so gelus of his wyue,</L><L>&THORN;at he ne myhte vor his lyue</L><L>Iseo &thorn;at mon wi&thorn; hire speke,</L><L N="1080">&THORN;at his heorte [n]olde breke.</L><L>He hire bilek in one bure,</L><L>&THORN;at hire was stronge &amp; sure: <PB N="93"></L><L>Ic hadde of hire [m]ilce &amp; ore,</L><L>And sori was for hire sore,</L><L N="1085">&amp; skente hi mid myne songe</L><L>Al &thorn;at ic mihte, ra&thorn;e &amp; longe.</L><L>Vor&thorn;an &thorn;e knyht wes wi&thorn; me wro&thorn;,</L><L>Vor rihte ny&thorn;e ic wes him lo&thorn;:</L><L>He dude me his owe schome,</L><L N="1090">Ac al hit turnde him eft to grome.</L><L>&THORN;at vnderyat &thorn;e kyng Henri:</L><L>Jesu his soule do mercy!</L><L>He let forbonne &thorn;ene knyht, <MILESTONE N="237r.1" UNIT="folio"></L><L>&THORN;at hadde ido svich vnriht</L><L N="1095">In so gode kynges londe;</L><L>For rihte ny&thorn;e &amp; ful onde</L><L>Let &thorn;ane lytel fowel nyme</L><L>&amp; him fordeme lif and lyme.</L><L>Hit wes w[u]r&thorn;sipe al myne kunne;</L><L N="1100">For&thorn;on &thorn;e kniht furles his w[u]nne,</L></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="supplied line groups"><HEAD TYPE="supplied">Lines 1101 through 1200</HEAD><L>&amp; yaf for me an hundred punde:</L><L>&amp; myne briddes seten ysunde, <PB N="95"></L><L>&amp; hedde se&thorn;&thorn;e blisse and hihte,</L><L>&amp; were bli&thorn;e, &amp; wel myhte.</L><L N="1105">Vor&thorn;an ic wes so wel awreke,</L><L>Euer eft ich dar &thorn;e bet speke:</L><L>For hit bitydde ene so,</L><L>Ich am &thorn;e bli&thorn;ure euer mo.</L><L>Nu ic may singe hwar ic wile,</L><L N="1110">Ne dar me neuer eft mon agrulle.</L><L>Ac &thorn;u, ermyng! &thorn;u wrecche gost!</L><L>&THORN;u ne canst fynde, ne &thorn;u nost,</L><L>An holeh stoc hwar &thorn;u &thorn;e mist hude,</L><L>&THORN;at me ne twenge &thorn;ine hude.</L><L N="1115">Vor children, gromes, heme &amp; hine,</L><L>Hi &thorn;enche&thorn; alle of &thorn;ine pine:</L><L>If hi mowe iseo &thorn;e sitte,</L><L>Stones hi do&thorn; in heore slytte,</L><L>&amp; &thorn;e totorue&thorn; &amp; tohene&thorn;,</L><L N="1120">&amp; &thorn;ine fule bon toschene&thorn;.</L><L>If &thorn;u art iworpe o&thorn;er iscote,</L><L>&THORN;enne &thorn;u myht erest to note.</L><L>Vor me &thorn;e ho&thorn; in one rodde,</L><L>&amp; &thorn;u, myd &thorn;ine fule codde,</L><L N="1125">&amp; myd &thorn;ine ateliche sweore,</L><L>Biwerest monne corn from deore. <PB N="97"></L><L>Nis nou&thorn;er nouht, &thorn;i lif ne blod: <MILESTONE N="237r.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L>Ac &thorn;u art sheules swi&thorn;e god.</L><L>&THORN;ar newe sedes beo&thorn; isowe,</L><L N="1130">Pynnuc, goldfynch, rok, ne crowe</L><L>Ne dar neuer cumen ihende,</L><L>If &thorn;i buk honge&thorn; at &thorn;an ende.</L><L>&THORN;ar treon schulle&thorn; ayer blowe,</L><L>&amp; yonge sedes springe &amp; growe,</L><L N="1135">Ne dar no fuoel &thorn;arto fonge,</L><L>If &thorn;u art &thorn;arouer ihonge.</L><L>&THORN;i lif is euer lu&thorn;er and qued,</L><L>&THORN;u nart nouht bute ded.</L><L>Nv &thorn;u myht wite sikerliche</L><L N="1140">&thorn;at &thorn;ine leches beo&thorn; grisliche</L><L>&THORN;e hwile &thorn;u art on lyfdaye:</L><L>Vor hwenne &thorn;u hongest islawe,</L><L>Yet hi beo&thorn; of &thorn;e atdradde,</L><L>&THORN;e foweles &thorn;at &thorn;e er bigradde.</L><L N="1145">Mid rihte men beo&thorn; wi&thorn; &thorn;e wro&thorn;e,</L><L>For &thorn;u singest of heore lo&thorn;e:</L><L>Al &thorn;at &thorn;u singest, ra&thorn;e o&thorn;er late,</L><L>Hit is euer of mannes vnhwate:</L><L>Hwanne &thorn;u hauest anyht igrad,</L><L N="1150">Men beo&thorn; of &thorn;e wel sore aferd. <PB N="99"></L><L>&THORN;u singst &thorn;ar sum man sal be ded:</L><L>Euer &thorn;u bodest sumne qued.</L><L>&THORN;u singst ayeyn ayhte lure,</L><L>O&thorn;er of summe vrendes rure:</L><L N="1155">O&thorn;er &thorn;u bodest huses brune,</L><L>O&thorn;er ferde of manne, o&thorn;er &thorn;eues run[e]:</L><L>O&thorn;er &thorn;u bodest qualm of orue,</L><L>O&thorn;er &thorn;at londfolc w[u]r&thorn; idorue,</L><L>O&thorn;er &thorn;at wif leost hire make:</L><L N="1160">O&thorn;er &thorn;u bodest cheste and sake.</L><L>Euer &thorn;u singest of manne harme, <MILESTONE N="237v.1" UNIT="folio"></L><L>&THORN;urh &thorn;e hi beo&thorn; sorie &amp; arme:</L><L>&THORN;u ne singest neuer one sy&thorn;e,</L><L>&THORN;at hit nys for summe vnsy&thorn;e.</L><L N="1165">Hervore hit is &thorn;at me &thorn;e sune&thorn;,</L><L>&amp; &thorn;e totorue&thorn; &amp; tobune&thorn;</L><L>Mid staue, &amp; stone, &amp; turf, &amp; clute,</L><L>&THORN;at &thorn;u ne myht noware atrute.</L><L>Dahet euer budel in tune</L><L N="1170">&THORN;at bede&thorn; vnwreste rune,</L><L>&amp; euer bringe&thorn; vuele tydinge,</L><L>&amp; &thorn;at speke&thorn; of vuele &thorn;inge!</L><L>God Almyhti w[u]r&thorn;e him wro&thorn;.</L><L>&amp; al &thorn;at were&thorn; lynnene clo&thorn;!"</L><L N="1175">   &THORN;e vle nabod noht swi&thorn;e longe,</L><L>Ac &yogh;ef answere stark &amp; stronge:</L><L>" Hwat," que&thorn; heo, "ertu ihoded?</L><L>O&thorn;er &thorn;u cursest vnihoded? <PB N="101"></L><L>For prestes wike ich wat &thorn;u dest.</L><L N="1180">Ich not if &thorn;u were preost:</L><L>Ich not if &thorn;u canst masse singe:</L><L>Inouh &thorn;u canst of Mansynge.</L><L>Ac hit is for &thorn;ine olde ny&thorn;e,</L><L>&THORN;at &thorn;u me acursedest o&thorn;er si&thorn;e:</L><L N="1185">Ac &thorn;arto is lihtlych answere:</L><L>"Drah to &thorn;e!" que&thorn; &thorn;e kartere.</L><L>Hwi atwitestu me myne insihte,</L><L>&amp; [m]in iwit &amp; myne myhte?</L><L>For ich am [witi] ful iwis,</L><L N="1190">&amp; wo[t] al &thorn;at to comen is.</L><L>Ich wot of hunger, of heregonge;</L><L>Ich wot if men sulle libbe longe;</L><L>Ich wot if wif lust hire make;</L><L>Ich wot hwar sal beo ni&thorn; &amp; wrake:</L><L N="1195">Ich wot hwo sal beo anhonge,</L><L>O&thorn;er elles fulne de&thorn; avonge.</L><L>If men habbe&thorn; batayle inume,</L><L>Ic w[o]t hwa&thorn;er sal beo ouercume; <MILESTONE N="237v.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L>Ic wot if qualm sal cumen on orve,</L><L N="1200">&amp; if deor schulle ligge astorue: <PB N="103"></L></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="supplied line groups"><HEAD TYPE="supplied">Lines 1201 through 1300</HEAD><L>Ic wot if tren schulle blowe:</L><L>Ic wot if corn schulle growe:</L><L>Ic wot if huses schulle berne:</L><L>Ic wot if men sulle eorne o&thorn;er erne:</L><L N="1205">Ic wot if sea sal sch[i]pes drenche:</L><L>Ic wot if [smithe] sale vuele clenche.</L><L>&amp; ic con muchele more:</L><L>Ic con ynouh in bokes lore,</L><L>&amp; ek ic can of &thorn;e Godspelle</L><L N="1210">More &thorn;an ic wile &thorn;e telle:</L><L>Vor ic at chireche cume ilome,</L><L>&amp; muchel leorny of wisdome:</L><L>Ic wot al of &thorn;e toknynge,</L><L>&amp; of o&thorn;er vale &thorn;inge.</L><L N="1215">If eny mon schal rem abide,</L><L>Al ic hit wot ar hit ityde. <PB N="105"></L><L>Ofte, vor myne muchele witte,</L><L>Wel sori-mod &amp; wro&thorn; I sytte:</L><L>Hwanne ic iseo &thorn;er sum wrecchede</L><L N="1220">Is cumynde neyh, inoh ic grede:</L><L>Ic bidde &thorn;er men beon warre,</L><L>&amp; habbe gode redes yare.</L><L>Vor Alured seyde a wis word,</L><L>Vych mon hit scholde legge on hord:</L><L N="1225">"If &thorn;u isyst her heo beo icume,</L><L>His streng&thorn;e is him wel neyh binume."</L><L>&amp; grete duntes beo&thorn; &thorn;e lasse,</L><L>If me ikepe&thorn; myd iwarnesse,</L><L>&amp; [flo] schal toward misyenge,</L><L N="1230">If &thorn;u isihst hw fleo of strenge:</L><L>For &thorn;u myht blenche &amp; fleo,</L><L>If &thorn;u isihst heo to &thorn;e teo.</L><L>&THORN;auh eny mon beo falle in edwite,</L><L>Hwi schal [he] me his sor atwite?</L><L N="1235">&THORN;auh ic iseo his harm bivore,</L><L>Ne cume&thorn; hit nouht of me &thorn;arfore.   fol. 238r. col.1.</L><L>&THORN;ah &thorn;u iseo &thorn;at sum blynd mon,</L><L>&THORN;at nanne rihtne wey ne con,</L><L>To &thorn;are diche his dwele volewe&thorn;,</L><L N="1240">&amp; falle&thorn;, &amp; &thorn;aronne sulie&thorn;, <PB N="107"></L><L>Wenestu, &thorn;ah ic al iseo,</L><L>&THORN;at hit for me &thorn;e ra&thorn;er beo?</L><L>Al so hit fare&thorn; bi [m]ine witte:</L><L>&THORN;anne ic on myne bowe sitte,</L><L N="1245">Ic wot &amp; iseo swi&thorn;e brihte</L><L>&THORN;at summe men cume&thorn; harm &thorn;arrihte.</L><L>Sal he, &thorn;ar he nowiht not,</L><L>Hit wite me vor ic hit wot?</L><L>Sal he his myshap wyten me,</L><L N="1250">Vor ic am wisure &thorn;an he?</L><L>Hwanne ic iseo &thorn;at sum wrechede</L><L>Is manne neyh, inouh ic grede,</L><L>&amp; bidde inouh &thorn;at hi heom schilde,</L><L>Vor toward heom is harm vnmylde.</L><L N="1255">Ac &thorn;ah ic grede lude and stille,</L><L>Al iwur&thorn; Godes wille.</L><L>Hwi wulle&thorn; men of me mene,</L><L>&THORN;ah ic mid so&thorn;e heo awene?</L><L>&THORN;ah ic hi warny al &thorn;at yer,</L><L N="1260">Nis heom &thorn;arvore [harem] &thorn;e ner:</L><L>Ac ich singe vor ich wolde</L><L>&THORN;er hi wel vnderstonde scholde</L><L>&THORN;at sum vnsel heom is ihende,</L><L>Hwen ic myn huyng to heom sende.</L><L N="1265">Naue&thorn; mon no sikerhede</L><L>&THORN;at he ne may wene &amp; adrede</L><L>&THORN;at sum vnhap neih him beo,</L><L>&THORN;ah he ne cunne hit iseo.</L><L>For&thorn;i seyde Alured swi&thorn;e wel,</L><L N="1270">&amp; his word was Godspel, <PB N="109"></L><L>&THORN;at "euerich mon, &thorn;e bet [him] beo,</L><L>Euer &thorn;e bet he him biseo": <MILESTONE N="238r.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L>"Ne triste no mon to his wele</L><L>To swi&thorn;e, &thorn;a[h] he habbe uele."</L><L N="1275">"Nis noht so hot &thorn;at hit nacole&thorn;,</L><L>Ne noht so hwit &thorn;at hit ne sole&thorn;,</L><L>Ne noht so leof &thorn;at hit nalo&thorn;e&thorn;,</L><L>Ne noht so glad &thorn;at hit nawre&thorn;e&thorn;:</L><L>Ac euerich &thorn;ing &thorn;at eche nys,</L><L N="1280">Agon schal, &amp; al &thorn;is worldes blis."</L><L>Nu &thorn;u miht witen redeliche,</L><L>&THORN;at euer &thorn;u spekest gidiliche:</L><L>For al &thorn;u me seyst vor schame,</L><L>Euer &thorn;e [solue] hit turne&thorn; to grome.</L><L N="1285">Go so hit go, at eche fenge</L><L>&THORN;u vallest myd &thorn;in owe swenge;</L><L>Al &thorn;at &thorn;u sayst for me to schende,</L><L>Hit is my w[u]r&thorn;sipe at &thorn;an ende.</L><L>Bute &thorn;u wille bet agynne,</L><L N="1290">Ne schaltu bute schame iwynne."</L><L>   &THORN;e nyhtegale sat and syhte,</L><L>&amp; hauhful was, &amp; wel myhte,</L><L>For &thorn;e vle so ispeke hadde,</L><L>And hire speche so iladde.</L><L N="1295">Heo wes houhful, and erede</L><L>Hwat heo &thorn;arafter hire seyde: <PB N="111"></L><L>Ac no&thorn;eles heo hire vnderstod.</L><L>"Hwat!" heo seyde, "vle, artu wod?</L><L>&THORN;u yelpest of selliche wisdome,</L><L N="1300">&THORN;u nustest hwenne hit &thorn;e come,</L></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="supplied line groups"><HEAD TYPE="supplied">Lines 1301 through 1400</HEAD><L>Bute hit of wicchecrafte were.</L><L>&THORN;arof &thorn;u, wrecche, most &thorn;e skere</L><L>If &thorn;u wilt among manne beo:</L><L>O&thorn;er &thorn;u most of londe fleo.</L><L N="1305">Vor alle &thorn;eo &thorn;at &thorn;erof cu&thorn;e,</L><L>Heo weren ifurn of prestes mu&thorn;e</L><L>Amansed: such [&thorn;u] art yette.</L><L>*    *    *    *    *    *</L><L>Ic &thorn;e seyde nv lutel ere,</L><L N="1310">&amp; &thorn;u askedest if ich were <MILESTONE N="238v.1" UNIT="folio"></L><L>A-bysemare to preoste ihoded.</L><L>Ac &thorn;e mansyng is so ibroded,</L><L>&THORN;auh no preost a-londe nere,</L><L>A wrecche na&thorn;eles &thorn;u were:</L><L N="1315">For euerich chi[l]d &thorn;e clepede fule,</L><L>&amp; euerich man a wrecche vle.</L><L>Ich habbe iherd, &amp; so&thorn; hit is,</L><L>&THORN;e mon mot beo wel sturre-wis,</L><L>&amp; wite inoh of hwiche &thorn;inge cume,</L><L N="1320">So &thorn;u seyst &thorn;at is iwune. <PB N="113"></L><L>Hwat constu, wr[e]cche &thorn;ing, of stor[r]e,</L><L>Bute &thorn;at &thorn;u biha[u]est hi ferre?</L><L>Al so do&thorn; mony deor and man,</L><L>&THORN;eo of suyche nowiht ne can.</L><L N="1325">On ape may on bok biholde,</L><L>&amp; leues wende and eft folde:</L><L>Ac he ne con &thorn;e bet &thorn;arvore</L><L>Of clerkes lore top ne more.</L><L>&THORN;ey &thorn;u iseo &thorn;e steorre al so,</L><L N="1330">Nertu &thorn;[e] wisere neuer &thorn;e mo.</L><L>Ac yet &thorn;u, fule &thorn;ing, me chist,</L><L>&amp; wel grimlyche me atwist</L><L>&THORN;at ic singe bi manne huse,</L><L>&amp; theche wyue breke spuse.</L><L N="1335">&THORN;u lyest iwis, &thorn;u fule &thorn;ing!</L><L>&THORN;urh me nes neuer isend spusing.</L><L>Ac so&thorn; hit is ich singe &amp; grede</L><L>&THORN;ar leuedis beo&thorn; &amp; feyre meide:</L><L>&amp; so&thorn; hit is of luue ich singe:</L><L N="1340">For god wif may in spusinge <PB N="115"></L><L>Bet luuyen hire owe were,</L><L>&THORN;an on o&thorn;er, hire copinere;</L><L>&amp; mayde may luue cheose</L><L>&THORN;at hire trevschipe ne forleose,</L><L N="1345">&amp; luuye mid rihte luue</L><L>&THORN;ane &thorn;at schal hire beo boue.</L><L>Suyche luue ic theche &amp; lere,</L><L>&THORN;erof beo&thorn; al myne ilere.        fol. 238v. col.2.</L><L>&THORN;auh sum wif beo of neysse mode,</L><L N="1350">Vor wymmen beo&thorn; of softe blode,</L><L>&THORN;at heo, vor summe sottes lore</L><L>&THORN;e yorne bit and syke&thorn; sore,</L><L>Misnyme &amp; misdo sume stunde,</L><L>Schal ic &thorn;arvore beo ibunde ?</L><L N="1355">Yef wymmen luuye&thorn; for vnrede,</L><L>Witestu me heore mysdede?</L><L>If wymmon &thorn;enche&thorn; luuye derne,</L><L>[Ne] may ic myne songes werne.</L><L>Wymmon may pleye vnder clo&thorn;e,</L><L N="1360">Hwe&thorn;er heo wile, wel &thorn;e wro&thorn;e:</L><L>&amp; heo may do bi [m]yne songe,</L><L>Hwe&thorn;er heo wile, wel &thorn;e wronge.</L><L>Vor nys a-worlde &thorn;ing so god,</L><L>&THORN;at ne may do sum vngod,</L><L N="1365">If me hit wile turne amys.</L><L>Vor gold &amp; seoluer, god hit is:</L><L>&amp; na&thorn;eles &thorn;armyd &thorn;u myht</L><L>Spusbruche bugge &amp; vnryht.</L><L>Wepne beo&thorn; gode gri&thorn; to holde:</L><L N="1370">&amp; na&thorn;eles &thorn;armyd beo&thorn; men aqolde <PB N="117"></L><L>Ayeynes riht of alle londe,</L><L>&THORN;ar &thorn;eoues hi bere&thorn; an honde.</L><L>Al so hit is bi myne songe,</L><L>&THORN;ah heo beo god, me hine may mysfonge,</L><L N="1375">&amp; drawe hine to sothede,</L><L>&amp; to o&thorn;re vuele dede.</L><L>Ah schaltu, wrecche, luue tele?</L><L>Beo hwich heo beo, vich luue is fele</L><L>Bitwene &thorn;e mon &amp; wymmone:</L><L N="1380">Ah if heo is abroyde, &thorn;eonne</L><L>He is vnvele and forbroyde.</L><L>Wro&thorn; wur&thorn;e him &thorn;e holy rode</L><L>&THORN;e rihte icunde so forbreyde&thorn;!</L><L>Wunder [hit is] &thorn;at heo ne awede&thorn;.</L><L N="1385">&amp; so heo do&thorn;, vor heo beo&thorn; wode,     fol.239r.col.1.</L><L>&THORN;at bute neste go&thorn; to brode.</L><L>Wymmon is of neysse fleysse,</L><L>&amp; fleysses [lust] is strong to queysse:</L><L>Nis wunder non &thorn;ah he abide.</L><L N="1390">Vor fleysses lustes hi make&thorn; slide,</L><L>Ne beo&thorn; heo nouht alle forlore</L><L>&THORN;at stumpe&thorn; at &thorn;e fleysses more:</L><L>Vor mony wymmon haue&thorn; mysdo</L><L>&THORN;at aryst vp of &thorn;e slo.</L><L N="1395">Ne beo&thorn; noht ones alle sunne,</L><L>Vor&thorn;an hi beo&thorn; tweire ikunne: <PB N="119"></L><L>Sum arist of fleysses luste,</L><L>&amp; sum of &thorn;e gostes custe.</L><L>&THORN;ar fleys drah&thorn; nv men to drunkenesse,</L><L N="1400">&amp; to [wrouehede] &amp; to golnesse,</L></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="supplied line groups"><HEAD TYPE="supplied">Lines 1401 through 1500</HEAD><L>&THORN;e gost mysdo&thorn; &thorn;urh ny&thorn; and onde,</L><L>&amp; se&thorn;&thorn;e myd [m]ureh&thorn;e of [monne shonde,] <PB N="121"></L><L>&amp; wunne&thorn; after more and more,</L><L>&amp; lutel rek&thorn; of [m]ilce and ore;</L><L N="1405">&amp; styh&thorn; on heyh &thorn;ur[h] modynesse,</L><L>&amp; ouerhowe&thorn; &thorn;ane lasse.</L><L>Sey me so&thorn;, if &thorn;u hit wost,</L><L>Hwe&thorn;er do&thorn; wurse, fleys &thorn;e gost?</L><L>&THORN;u myht segge, if &thorn;u wult,</L><L N="1410">&THORN;at lasse is &thorn;es fley[s]es gult:</L><L>Mony mon is of his fleysse clene,</L><L>&THORN;at is myd mode deouel-imene.</L><L>Ne schal no mon wymman bigrede,</L><L>&amp; fleysses lustes hire vpbreyde:</L><L N="1415">Such heo mahte beo of golnesse,</L><L>&thorn;at sunege&thorn; wurse in modinesse.</L><L>Hwet if ic schulde a-luue bringe</L><L>Wif o&thorn;er mayde, hwanne ic singe?</L><L>Ic wolde wi&thorn; &thorn;e mayde holde,</L><L N="1420">If &thorn;u const aryht atholde:</L><L>Lust nv, ic segge &thorn;e hwarvore,</L><L>Vp to &thorn;e toppe from &thorn;e more.    fol.239r. col.2.</L><L>If mayde luue&thorn; derneliche,</L><L>Heo stumpe&thorn; &amp; fal&thorn; icundeliche:</L><L N="1425">Vor &thorn;aih heo sum hwile pleye,</L><L>Heo nys noht feor vt of &thorn;e weye;</L><L>Heo may hire guld atwende</L><L>A rihte weye &thorn;urh chirche-bende,</L><L>&amp; may eft habbe to make</L><L N="1430">Hire leofmon wi&thorn;vte sake, <PB N="123"></L><L>&amp; gon to him bi dayes lyhte,</L><L>&THORN;at er bistal on &thorn;eoster nyhte.</L><L>&THORN;at yongling not hwat such &thorn;ing is:</L><L>His yonge blod hit drah&thorn; amys,</L><L N="1435">&amp; sum sot man hit tyh&thorn; &thorn;arto</L><L>Mid alle &thorn;an &thorn;at he may do.</L><L>He cume&thorn; &amp; fare&thorn; and beod abid,</L><L>&amp; he bistarte an o&thorn;er sid,</L><L>&amp; bisek&thorn; ilome and longe.</L><L N="1440">Hwat may &thorn;at child &thorn;ah hit misfonge?</L><L>Hit nuste neuer hwat hi[t] was,</L><L>Vor&thorn;i hit &thorn;ouhte fondi &thorn;as,</L><L>&amp; wyte iwis hwich beo &thorn;e gome</L><L>&THORN;at of &thorn;e wilde make&thorn; tome.</L><L N="1445">Ne may ic vor reu&thorn;e lete,</L><L>Hwanne ic iseo &thorn;e tohte ilete</L><L>&THORN;e luue bring on [&thorn;]e [y]unglinge,</L><L>&THORN;at ic of mureh&thorn;e him ne singe.</L><L>Ic theche heom bi myne songe</L><L N="1450">&THORN;at suych luue ne last noht longe:</L><L>For my song lu[tl]e wile ileste,</L><L>&amp; luue ne do&thorn; noht bute reste <PB N="125"></L><L>On such childre, &amp; sone age&thorn;,</L><L>&amp; fal&thorn; adun &thorn;e [hote] bre&thorn;.</L><L N="1455">I singe myd heom one &thorn;rowe,</L><L>Biginne an heyh &amp; endi lowe,</L><L>&amp; lete mine songes falle</L><L>A lu[tl]e wi[l]e adun myd alle.</L><L>&THORN;at mayde wot, hwenne I s[w]ike,    fol. 239v. col.1.</L><L N="1460">[&THORN;at] luue is myne songes ili[k]e,</L><L>Vor hit nys bute a lutel bre&thorn;,</L><L>&THORN;at sone cume&thorn;, and sone ge&thorn;.</L><L>&THORN;at child bi me hit vnderstond,</L><L>&amp; his vnred to rede iwend,</L><L N="1465">&amp; syh&thorn; wel, bi myne songe,</L><L>&THORN;at dusy luue ne last noht longe.</L><L>Ac wel ic wile &thorn;at &thorn;u hit wite,</L><L>Lo&thorn; me beo&thorn; wifes vtschute:</L><L>Ac wif may of me nyme yeme,</L><L N="1470">Ic ne singe noht hwen ic teme.</L><L>&amp; wif auh lete sottes lore,</L><L>&THORN;auh spusyng-bendes bynde&thorn; sore.</L><L>Wunder me &thorn;ink&thorn; stark &amp; sor,</L><L>Hw eny mon so haue&thorn; for</L><L N="1475">&THORN;at his heorte myhte dryue</L><L>To do hit to o&thorn;res mannes wyue:</L><L>Vor o&thorn;er hit is of twam &thorn;inge,</L><L>Ne may &thorn;e &thorn;ridde no mon bringe;</L><L>O&thorn;er &thorn;e louerd is wel auht,</L><L N="1480">O&thorn;er aswunde, &amp; nys nouht.</L><L>If he is w[u]r&thorn;ful &amp; auht mon,</L><L>Nele no mon, &thorn;at wisdom can, <PB N="127"></L><L>Hure of his wive do him schome:</L><L>Vor he may him adrede grame,</L><L N="1485">&amp; &thorn;at he forleose &thorn;at &thorn;er honge&thorn;,</L><L>&THORN;at him eft &thorn;arto noht ne longe&thorn;.</L><L>&amp; &thorn;ah he &thorn;at nouht ne adrede&thorn;,</L><L>Hit is vnriht &amp; gret sothede</L><L>To mysdo one gode manne,</L><L N="1490">&amp; his ibedde from him spanne.</L><L>If hire louerd is forwur&thorn;e</L><L>&amp; vnorne at bedde &amp; at borde,</L><L>Hw myhte &thorn;ar beo eny luue</L><L>Hwenne a cherles buk hire lay buue?</L><L N="1495">Hw may &thorn;er eny luue beo, <MILESTONE N="239v.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L>Hwar such mon grope&thorn; hire &thorn;eo?</L><L>Herbi &thorn;u miht wel vnderstonde</L><L>&THORN;at on is at &thorn;en o&thorn;res schonde</L><L>To stele to o&thorn;res mannes bedde.</L><L N="1500">Vor if auht man is hire ibedde,</L></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="supplied line groups"><HEAD TYPE="supplied">Lines 1501 through 1600</HEAD><L>&THORN;u myht wene &thorn;at &thorn;e mystide,</L><L>Hwanne &thorn;u lyst bi hire side.</L><L>&amp; if &thorn;e louerd is a wrecche,</L><L>Hwych este myhtestu &thorn;ar vecche? <PB N="129"></L><L N="1505">If &thorn;u bi&thorn;enchest hwo hire ofligge,</L><L>&THORN;u myht myd wlate &thorn;e este bugge.</L><L>Ich not hw may eny freomon</L><L>Vor hire sechen after &thorn;an.</L><L>If he bi&thorn;enk&thorn; bi hwam he lay,</L><L N="1510">Al may &thorn;e luue gon away."</L><L>   &THORN;e vle wes glad of suche tale:</L><L>Heo &thorn;ouhte &thorn;at &thorn;e nyhtegale,</L><L>&THORN;ah heo wel speke at &thorn;e frume,</L><L>Hadde at &thorn;an ende mysnume:</L><L N="1515">&amp; seyde "Nv ich habbe ifunde</L><L>&THORN;at maydenes beo&thorn; of &thorn;in imunde:</L><L>Mid heom &thorn;u holdest, &amp; heom biwerest</L><L>&amp; ouerswi&thorn;e &thorn;u hi herest.</L><L>&THORN;e lauedies beo&thorn; to me iwend,</L><L N="1520">To me hire mone heo send.</L><L>For hit ityd ofte and ilome,</L><L>&THORN;at wif &amp; were beo&thorn; vnisome:</L><L>&amp; &thorn;erfore &thorn;at were gulte,</L><L>&THORN;at leof is o&thorn;er wymmon to pulte,</L><L N="1525">&amp; spene&thorn; on &thorn;are al &thorn;at he haue&thorn;,</L><L>&amp; sywe&thorn; &thorn;are &thorn;at noht naue&thorn;, <PB N="131"></L><L>&amp; haue&thorn; atom his riche spuse,</L><L>Wowes west, and lere huse,</L><L>Wel &thorn;unne isrud &amp; ived wro&thorn;e,</L><L N="1530">&amp; let heo bute mete &amp; clo&thorn;e.</L><L>Hwenne he cume&thorn; hom eft to his wyue,</L><L>Ne dar he noht a word ischire: <MILESTONE N="240r.1" UNIT="folio"></L><L>He chid &amp; gred such he beo wod,</L><L>&amp; ne bring&thorn; hom non o&thorn;er god.</L><L N="1535">Al &thorn;at heo do&thorn; him is vnwille,</L><L>Al &thorn;at heo speke&thorn; hit is him ille:</L><L>&amp; ofte hwenne heo noht ne mysde&thorn;,</L><L>Heo haue&thorn; &thorn;e fust in &thorn;e the&thorn;.</L><L>Nis nomon &thorn;at ne may ibrynge</L><L N="1540">His wif amys myd suche &thorn;inge:</L><L>Me hire may so ofte mysbeode,</L><L>&THORN;at heo do wile hire owe neode.</L><L>La, God hit wot! heo nah iwelde,</L><L>&THORN;ah heo hine make cukeweld.</L><L N="1545">For hit ityt ilome and ofte,</L><L>&THORN;at his wif is neysse &amp; softe,</L><L>Of fayre bleo &amp; wel idiht:</L><L>[For]&thorn;i hit is &thorn;e more vnryht</L><L>&THORN;at he is [luue] spene on &thorn;are,</L><L N="1550">&THORN;at nis wur&thorn; on of hire heare.</L><L>&amp; suche men beo&thorn; wel manyfolde,</L><L>&THORN;at wif ne cunne ariht holde.</L><L>Ne mot no mon wi&thorn; hire speke:</L><L>He wene&thorn; heo wile anon tobreke</L><L N="1555">Hire spusyng, if heo loke&thorn;</L><L>O&thorn;er wi&thorn; manne veyre speke&thorn;. <PB N="133"></L><L>He hire biluk&thorn; myd keye &amp; loke:</L><L>&THORN;ar-&thorn;urh is spusing ofte ibroke.</L><L>Vor if heo is &thorn;arto ibrouht,</L><L N="1560">He de&thorn; &thorn;at heo nedde ear i&thorn;ouht.</L><L>Dehaet &thorn;at to swi&thorn;e hit bispeke,</L><L>&THORN;ah suche wiues heom awreke!</L><L>Herof to me &thorn;e leuedies heom mene&thorn;,</L><L>And wel sore me ahwene&thorn;:</L><L N="1565">Wel neyh myn heorte wile tochine,</L><L>Hwenne ic biholde heore [pine].</L><L>Mid heom ic wepe swi&thorn;e sore,</L><L>&amp; for heom bidde Cristes ore,</L><L>&THORN;at &thorn;e leuedi sone aredde <MILESTONE N="240r.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L N="1570">&amp; hire sende betere ibedde.   </L><L>An o&thorn;er &thorn;ing ic may &thorn;e telle,</L><L>&amp; &thorn;u ne schalt, for &thorn;ine felle,</L><L>Onswere non &thorn;arto fynde:</L><L>Al &thorn;is sputing schal aswinde.</L><L N="1575">Mony chapmon &amp; mony knyht</L><L>Luue&thorn; &amp; halt his wif ariht,</L><L>&amp; so do&thorn; mony bondeman:</L><L>&THORN;at gode wif do&thorn; after &thorn;an,</L><L>&amp; sarue&thorn; him to bedde &amp; to borde</L><L N="1580">Mid fayre dede &amp; fayre worde,</L><L>&amp; yorne vonde&thorn; hw heo mowe</L><L>Do &thorn;ing &thorn;at him beo iduwe.</L><L>&THORN;e louerd into &thorn;are &thorn;eode</L><L>Vare&thorn; vt on &thorn;are beyre neode,</L><L N="1585">&amp; is &thorn;at gode wif vnbli&thorn;e</L><L>Vor hire louerdes hou[h]sy&thorn;e, <PB N="135"></L><L>&amp; sit &amp; syk&thorn; wel sore oflonged,</L><L>&amp; hire sore an heorte ongre&thorn;:</L><L>Al vor hire louerdes sake</L><L N="1590">Haue&thorn; dayes kare &amp; nihtes wake:</L><L>&amp; swi&thorn;e longe hire is &thorn;e hwile,</L><L>&amp; vych stape hire &thorn;ink&thorn; a [m]ile.</L><L>Hwenne o&thorn;re slepe&thorn; hire abute,</L><L>Ich one lust &thorn;ar wy&thorn;&thorn;ute,</L><L N="1595">&amp; wot of hire sore mode,</L><L>&amp; singe anyht for hire gode:</L><L>&amp; myn gode song, for hire &thorn;inge,</L><L>Ic turne sumdel to [m]urnynge.</L><L>Of hure seorwe ic bere sume,</L><L N="1600">Vor&thorn;an ic am hire wel welcume:</L></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="supplied line groups"><HEAD TYPE="supplied">Lines 1601 through 1700</HEAD><L>Ic hire helpe hwat ich may,</L><L>For [ho ge&thorn;] &thorn;ane rihte way.</L><L>&amp; &thorn;u me hauest sore igremed,</L><L>&THORN;at myn heorte is neyh alemed,</L><L N="1605">&THORN;at ic may vnne&thorn;e speke:</L><L>Ac yet ic wile for&thorn;urre reke. <MILESTONE N="240v.1" UNIT="folio"></L><L>&THORN;u seyst &thorn;at ic am monne lo&thorn;,</L><L>&amp; vich mon is wi&thorn; me wro&thorn;,</L><L>&amp; me myd stone &amp; lugge &thorn;rete&thorn;,</L><L N="1610">&amp; me toburste[&thorn;] &amp; tobete[&thorn;], <PB N="137"></L><L>&amp; hwanne hi habbe&thorn; me ofslawe,</L><L>Heo anho&thorn; me in heore hawe,</L><L>&THORN;ar ich aschevle pie &amp; crowe</L><L>From &thorn;an &thorn;at &thorn;er is isowe.</L><L N="1615">&THORN;ah hit beo so&thorn;, ic do heom god,</L><L>&amp; for heom ic schedde my blod:</L><L>Ic do heom god myd myne de&thorn;e,</L><L>&THORN;arfore &thorn;e is wel unme&thorn;e.</L><L>For [&thorn;ah] &thorn;u ligge ded &amp; clinge,</L><L N="1620">&THORN;i de&thorn; nys nouht to none &thorn;inge:</L><L>Ic not neuer to hwan &thorn;u myht,</L><L>For &thorn;u nart bute a wreche wiht.</L><L>Ah &thorn;ah my lif me beo atschote,</L><L>&THORN;e yet ic may do gode note:</L><L N="1625">Me may vppe smale sticke</L><L>Me sette a-wude ine &thorn;e &thorn;ikke,</L><L>&amp; so may mon tolli him to</L><L>Lutle briddes and ivo,</L><L>&amp; so me may myd me byete</L><L N="1630">Wel gode brede to his mete.</L><L>Ah &thorn;u neuer mon to gode</L><L>Lyues ne de&thorn;es stal ne stode: <PB N="139"></L><L>Ic not to hwan &thorn;u breist &thorn;i word,</L><L>Lyues ne de&thorn;es ne do&thorn; hit god."</L><L N="1635">   &THORN;e Nihtegale iherde &thorn;is,</L><L>&amp; hupte vppe on blowe ris,</L><L>&amp; herre sat &thorn;ane heo dude er:</L><L>"Vle," he seyde, "beo nv wer, <MILESTONE N="240v.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L>Nule ic wi&thorn; &thorn;e playdi namore,</L><L N="1640">Vor her &thorn;u myst &thorn;i ryhte lore:</L><L>&THORN;[u] yelpest &thorn;at &thorn;u art monne lo&thorn;,</L><L>&amp; euervich wiht is wi&thorn; &thorn;e wro&thorn;:</L><L>&amp; myd yollinge &amp; myd igrede</L><L>&THORN;u &thorn;inchst wel &thorn;at &thorn;u art vnlede.</L><L N="1645">&THORN;u seyst &thorn;at gromes &thorn;e ivo&thorn;,</L><L>&amp; heye on rode &thorn;e anho&thorn;,</L><L>&amp; &thorn;e totwicche&thorn; &amp; toschake&thorn;,</L><L>&amp; summe of &thorn;e scheules make&thorn;.</L><L>Me &thorn;ink&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;u forlest &thorn;at game,</L><L N="1650">&THORN;u yelpest of &thorn;ire owe schome:</L><L>Me &thorn;ink&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;u me gest an honde,</L><L>&THORN;u yelpest of &thorn;ine owe schonde."</L><L>&THORN;o heo hadde &thorn;eos word [icwede],</L><L>Heo sat in one fayre stude,</L><L N="1655">&amp; &thorn;arafter hire stefne dihte,</L><L>&amp; song so schille &amp; so brihte, <PB N="141"></L><L>&THORN;at fur &amp; neor me hit iherde.</L><L>&THORN;arvore anon to hire cherde</L><L>&THORN;ruysse &amp; &thorn;rostle &amp; wodewale,</L><L N="1660">&amp; foweles bo&thorn;e grete &amp; smale:</L><L>Vor&thorn;an &thorn;at heom &thorn;uhte &thorn;at heo hadde</L><L>&THORN;e vle ouercome, for&thorn;an heo gradde</L><L>&amp; sungen also uale wise,</L><L>&THORN;at blisse wes among &thorn;e ryse.</L><L N="1665">Riht so me gred &thorn;e monne a schame,</L><L>&THORN;at tauele&thorn; &amp; forleost &thorn;at gome.</L><L>   &THORN;eos vle, &thorn;o heo &thorn;is iherde,</L><L>" Hauestu," heo seyde, "ibanned ferde?</L><L>&amp; wiltu, wrecche, wi&thorn; me vyhte?</L><L N="1670">Na, nay! nauestu none [m]ihte! <MILESTONE N="241r.1" UNIT="folio"></L><L>Hwat grede&thorn; heo &thorn;at hider come?</L><L>Me &thorn;ink&thorn; &thorn;u ledest ferde to me.</L><L>Ye schulle wite, ar ye fleo heonne,</L><L>Hwuch is &thorn;e streng&thorn;e of myne kunne:</L><L N="1675">Vor &thorn;eo &thorn;at haue&thorn; bile ihoked,</L><L>&amp; clyures scharpe &amp; wel icroked,</L><L>Alle heo beo&thorn; of myne kunrede,</L><L>&amp; wolde cumen if ich bede. <PB N="143"></L><L>&THORN;e seolue cok, &thorn;at wel can vihte,</L><L N="1680">He mot myd me holde wi&thorn; rihte,</L><L>Vor [bo&thorn;e] we habbe stefne brihte,</L><L>&amp; sitte&thorn; vnder welkne bi nyhte.</L><L>Schulle ic up eu on vtest grede,</L><L>Ich schal swo stronge verde lede,</L><L N="1685">&THORN;at oure prude schal aualle;</L><L>A tord ne yeue ic for eu alle!</L><L>Ne schal, ar hit beo fullich eue,</L><L>A wrecche ve&thorn;ere on eu bileue.</L><L>Ah hit wes vnker uoreward,</L><L N="1690">&THORN;o we comen hyderward,</L><L>&THORN;at we &thorn;arto holden scholde,</L><L>&THORN;ar riht dom vs yeue wolde.</L><L>Wultu nv breke foreward?</L><L>Ic wene dom &thorn;e &thorn;ink&thorn; to hard.</L><L N="1695">Vor &thorn;u ne darst domes abyde,</L><L>&THORN;u wilt nv, wreche, fihte &amp; chide.</L><L>Yet ich eu wolde alle rede,</L><L>Ar ich uthest vp eu grede, <PB N="145"></L><L>&THORN;at eur fihtlac lete&thorn; beo,</L><L N="1700">&amp; gynne&thorn; ra&thorn;e ayeyn fleo.</L></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="supplied line groups"><HEAD TYPE="supplied">Lines 1701 through 1794</HEAD><L>Vor, bi &thorn;e clyures &thorn;at ic bere,</L><L>If ye abide&thorn; myne here,</L><L>Ye schulle&thorn; an o&thorn;er wise singe,</L><L>&amp; cursy alle fihtinge:</L><L N="1705">Vor nys of ou non so kene,</L><L>&THORN;at durre abide myn onsene."</L><L>&THORN;eos vle spak wel baldelyche,</L><L>Vor &thorn;ah heo nadde so hwatliche</L><L>Iuare after hire here, <MILESTONE N="241r.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L N="1710">Heo wolde na&thorn;eles yeue answere     </L><L>&THORN;e [n]ihtegale myd sweche worde.</L><L>For mony mon myd speres orde</L><L>Haue&thorn; lutle streng&thorn;e, &amp; mid his schelde,</L><L>Ah na&thorn;eles in one felde,</L><L N="1715">&THORN;urh belde worde &amp; myd ilete,</L><L>De&thorn; is iuo for areh&thorn;e swete.</L><L>&THORN;e wrenne, for heo cu&thorn;e singe,</L><L>&THORN;ar com in &thorn;are moreweninge</L><L>To helpe &thorn;are nyhtegale:</L><L N="1720">Vor [&thorn;eih] heo hadde stefne smale,</L><L>Heo hadde gode &thorn;rote &amp; schille,</L><L>&amp; fale monne song a wille.</L><L>&THORN;e wrenne wes wel wis iholde,</L><L>Vor &thorn;eih heo nere ibred a-wolde,</L><L N="1725">Heo wes itowen among mankunne,</L><L>&amp; hire wisdom brouhte &thorn;enne:</L><L>Heo myhte speke hwar heo wolde,</L><L>Tofore &thorn;e kinge &thorn;ah heo scholde. <PB N="147"></L><L>"Luste&thorn;," heo que&thorn;, "lete&thorn; me speke.</L><L N="1730">Hwat! wille ye &thorn;is pays tobreke,</L><L>&amp; do &thorn;anne [kinge] such schome?</L><L>Yet nys heo nou&thorn;er ded ne lome.</L><L>Hunke schal ityde harm &amp; schonde,</L><L>If we do&thorn; gry&thorn;bruche on his londe.</L><L N="1735">Lete&thorn; beo, &amp; beo&thorn; isome,</L><L>&amp; fare&thorn; riht to eure dome,</L><L>&amp; lete&thorn; dom &thorn;is playd tobreke,</L><L>Al so hit wes erure bispeke."</L><L>   "Ich vnne wel," que&thorn; &thorn;e Nihtegale,</L><L N="1740">"Ah, wrenne, nouht for &thorn;ine tale,</L><L>Ac do myre lauhfulnesse.</L><L>Ic nolde &thorn;at vnrihtfulnesse</L><L>Me at &thorn;en ende [ouercome]:</L><L>Ic nam ofdred of none dome.</L><L N="1745">Bihote ic habbe, so&thorn; hit is,</L><L>&THORN;at Mayster Nichole, &thorn;at is wis,</L><L>Bitwihen [us] deme schulle,</L><L>&amp; yet ic wene &thorn;at he wulle. <MILESTONE N="241v.1" UNIT="folio"></L><L>Ah [w]ar myhte we hine fynde?"</L><L N="1750">&THORN;e wrenne sat in hore lynde: <PB N="149"></L><L>"Hwat! [nute ye]," qua&thorn; heo, "his hom?</L><L>Heo wune&thorn; at Porteshom,</L><L>At one tune in Dorsete,</L><L>Bi &thorn;are see in ore vtlete:</L><L N="1755">&THORN;ar he deme&thorn; mony riht dom,</L><L>&amp; diht &amp; wryt mony wisdom,</L><L>&amp; &thorn;urh his mu&thorn;e &amp; &thorn;urh his honde</L><L>Hit is &thorn;e betere into Scotlonde.</L><L>To seche hyne is lyhtlych &thorn;ing;</L><L N="1760">He naue&thorn; buten o wunyng.</L><L>&THORN;at is biscopen muchel schame,</L><L>&amp; alle &thorn;an &thorn;at of his nome</L><L>Habbe&thorn; iherd, and of his dede.</L><L>Hwi nulle&thorn; hi nymen heom to rede,</L><L N="1765">&THORN;at he were myd heom ilome</L><L>Vor teche heom of his wisdome,</L><L>&amp; yeue him rente on vale stude,</L><L>&THORN;at he myhte ilome heom beo myde?" <PB N="151"></L><L>   "Certes," qua&thorn; &thorn;e vle, "&thorn;at is so&thorn;:</L><L N="1770">&THORN;eos riche men [m]uchel mysdo&thorn;,</L><L>&THORN;at lete&thorn; &thorn;ane gode man,</L><L>&THORN;at of so fele &thorn;inge can,</L><L>&amp; yeue&thorn;rente wel [m]islyche,</L><L>&amp; of him lete&thorn; wel lyhtliche.</L><L N="1775">Wi&thorn; heore kunne heo beo&thorn; [m]ildre,</L><L>&amp; yeue&thorn; rente lutle childre:</L><L>So heore wit hi deme&thorn; a-dwole,</L><L>&THORN;at euer abit Mayster Nichole.</L><L>Ah vte we &thorn;ah to hym fare,</L><L N="1780">Vor &thorn;a[r] is vnker dom al yare."</L><L>   "Do we," &thorn;e Nihtegale seyde:</L><L>"Ah hwo schal vnker speche rede,</L><L>&amp; telle tovore vnker d[e]me?"</L><L>   "&THORN;arof ic schal &thorn;e wel iqueme,"</L><L N="1785">Que&thorn; &thorn;e vle; "for al, ende of orde, <MILESTONE N="241v.2" UNIT="folio"></L><L>Telle ic con, word after worde:</L><L>&amp; if &thorn;e &thorn;ink&thorn; &thorn;at ic misrempe,</L><L>&THORN;u stond ayeyn and do me crempe."</L><L>Mid &thorn;isse worde for&thorn; hi ferden,</L><L N="1790">Al bute here and bute verde,</L><L>To Portesham &thorn;er heo bicome.</L><L>Ah hw heo spedde of heore dome,</L><L>Ne can ic eu namore telle;</L><L>Her nys namore of &thorn;isse spelle.</L></DIV1><TRAILER>Explicit</TRAILER></BODY></TEXT></TEI.2>